"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650387","Department for Education","false","2016-12-12","<p>Departmental officials have discussed this matter with the exam board and it is for individual boards to decide which qualifications to offer. It is disappointing that no board has come forward to develop a new A-level in archaeology for teaching from 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The option for an exam board to develop qualifications in this subject in future will remain open. Archaeology A-level is not a pre-requisite for degree level study in the subject, and it is taken by a small number of students – 340 in 2015/16.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-12-12T16:26:48.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650387/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650387/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-02","Archaeology: GCE A-level","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are having discussions with examination boards about the possible continuation of the Archaeology A-level.","false","Biography information for The Earl of Clancarty",,"The Earl of Clancarty","HL3777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650388","Department for Education","false","2016-12-16","<p>We will be publishing the full list of providers eligible for three-year allocations, and the allocations by subject and route in due course. This information will comprise data on both primary and secondary phase, inclusive of all provider-led and school direct trainee places.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-12-16T13:16:38.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650388/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650388/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650388/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-12-02","Teachers: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which initial teacher training providers were allocated places for three years from 2017–18; and how many places were allocated to each provider (1) apportioned by primary and secondary phases, and (2) broken down by individual secondary subject.","false","Biography information for Baroness Donaghy",,"Baroness Donaghy","HL3778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650389","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>No, we have not considered this. Local authorities are already obliged to consult on proposals for development in their area; the consultation period usually lasts for 21 days and we believe this period strikes an appropriate balance between ensuring sufficient consultation with the community and an efficient determination period for the applicant.</p><p>However, where statutory consultation is required<strong>,</strong> article 22(3) of the Town and Country Planning (Development Management Procedure) (England) Order 2015 gives local authorities and statutory consultees the opportunity to agree in writing to a period other than 21 days in which to provide responses if necessary.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T12:12:15.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650389/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650389/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-02","Planning Permission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have considered advising local authorities to extend the consultation period of planning applications which include bank holiday periods; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gardner of Parkes",,"Baroness Gardner of Parkes","HL3779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650390","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-15","<p>By the end of the Parliament, local government will retain 100 per cent of taxes raised locally, giving councils control of additional £12.5 billion of business rates to spend on local services. To ensure the reforms are fiscally neutral, new responsibilities will be devolved to local authorities. We recently conducted a consultation on our approach to the implementation of 100 per cent Business Rates Retention. There were over 450 responses, including 26 from individual London boroughs and a joint response from the Greater London Authority and London Councils. My officials are currently considering all responses and we will publish a summary of the responses and our proposals for the broad way forward in due course.</p><p>In the meantime, we will continue close collaboration with local government in taking this work forward, including through the Business Rates Retention Steering Group, which is jointly chaired by the Local Government Association (LGA) and the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG). The Steering Group was established to consider the mechanisms needed to set up and run the new business rates system, as well as the timetable and implementation of the reforms. It oversees the work of a set of technical working groups, each looking at particular aspects of the reforms. The Group meets on a regular basis and has done so on 7 occasions since April 2016. All papers for meetings are published here:</p><p><a href="http://www.local.gov.uk/business-rates" target="_blank">http://www.local.gov.uk/business-rates</a></p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-15T17:13:21.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650390/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650390/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-02","Non-domestic Rates: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest estimate of the effect on London local authority budgets of the proposed retention of business rates.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kennedy of Cradley",,"Baroness Kennedy of Cradley","HL3780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650391","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Autumn Statement announced an expansion of the Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme (SOAHP) 2016-21, allocating an additional £1.4 billion to the programme for a further 40,000 housing starts by 2021. We remain committed to Shared Ownership which has an important role to play, but it is important that government also enables providers to deliver a variety of tenures that support a wide range of people in different circumstances.</p><p>Page 51 of the OBR's &quot;Economic and fiscal outlook&quot; refers to its assessment of the impact of this change. The Office for Budget Responsibility’s (OBR) has taken one particular approach to its forecasting model, but would themselves acknowledge the uncertainty around their forecast. It will review its forecast as new data becomes available.</p><p>Housing associations themselves are saying that the tenure flexibility and funding will help them build more and the National Housing Federation has said it &quot;will give housing associations the freedom and confidence to build even more affordable homes, more quickly, across the country''.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T12:11:32.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650391/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650391/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-02","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the Office for Budget Responsibility comments on page 51 of their report <i>Economic and fiscal outlook,</i> published on 23 November, regarding housebuilding and residential investment.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650392","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-15","<p>In March, the government published the sector-produced Local Government Counter Fraud and Corruption Strategy. This set out a series of recommendations encouraging councils, to enhance their capability to tackle all types of fraud including Council Tax. In November the government published the National Fraud Initiative report which detailed the cancellation, by local authorities, of over 37,000 Council Tax Single Person Discount claims for fraud and error over the last two years as a result of the data matches provided by NFI. £11 million of underpayments are being recovered and future underpayments of £24 million have been prevented.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-15T17:06:43.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650392/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650392/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-02","Council Tax: Fraud","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to assist local authorities to combat council tax fraud.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650393","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-12","<p>At Autumn Statement 2016, the Chancellor announced a large-scale regional pilot of the voluntary Right to Buy, which will be funded by the government.</p><p>In terms of the main scheme, we have engaged closely with local authorities in the development of how we fund the extension of Right to Buy to housing association tenants. We are considering how the policy will be implemented under the Housing and Planning Act 2016 and will continue to engage with local authorities and other stakeholders as we develop the detail.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-12T15:10:49.75Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650393/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650393/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-02","Right to Buy Scheme: Housing Associations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 28 November (HL3302), what discussions they are having with local authorities as the funders of the Right to Buy scheme.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650394","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>The Estate Regeneration Advisory Panel has met five times since February 2016. A number of Advisory Panel sub-groups have also met to consider issues such as resident engagement, finance</p><p>and design. The Advisory Panel has informed the Estate Regeneration National Strategy.</p><p>The following are members of the Estate Regeneration Advisory Panel:</p><p>Councillor Ravi Govindia, Leader of Wandsworth Council.</p><p>Nicholas Boys Smith, Director of Create Streets.</p><p>Andrew Boff, Leader of the Greater London Authority Conservatives housing group.</p><p>Elaine Bailey, Chief Executive of Hyde Housing Association.</p><p>Paul Tennant, Chief Executive of Orbit Housing Association.</p><p>Tony Pidgley CBE, Chairman of the Berkeley Group.</p><p>Peter Vernon, Chief Executive of Grosvenor Britain &amp; Ireland.</p><p>Jane Duncan, President of the Royal Institute of British Architects.</p><p>Ben Bolgar, Senior Director at the Prince’s Foundation.</p><p>Dominic Grace, Head of London Residential Development at Savills.</p><p>Emma Cariaga, Project Director at British Land.</p><p>David Budd, Mayor of Middlesbrough.</p><p>Natalie Elphicke OBE, Chief Executive of the Housing &amp; Finance Institute.</p><p>Graham Allen MP, Member of Parliament for Nottingham North.</p><p>Félicie Krikler, Director at Assael Architecture.</p><p>Lord Andrew Mawson, Director of Andrew Mawson Partnerships.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T12:10:34.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650394/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650394/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-02","Estates Regeneration Advisory Panel","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 17 November (HL3179), who are the members of the Estate Regeneration Advisory Panel, and how many meetings have been held so far in this financial year.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650395","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-19","<p>Eighty seven pocket parks have been created in predominantly deprived neighbourhoods under the government funded pocket parks programme.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-19T12:10:51.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650395/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650395/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-12-02","Parks","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth on 27 October (HL2320), how many Pocket Parks have been delivered to date.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650396","Department of Health","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) does not have any immediate plans to increase requirements or penalties for hygiene standards.</p><p> </p><p>However, though the FSA’s ‘Regulating Our Future’ programme it is working to reform and improve the current regulatory system, thus making sure that people have safe food, food they can trust, and that it is what it says it is.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-15T12:50:20.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650396/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650396/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-02","Food: Hygiene","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to strengthen the requirements and penalties relating to the meeting of hygiene standards by food businesses.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650397","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>We are clear that our scheme will prioritise the most vulnerable refugees, and that is why under the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Resettlement (VPR) scheme the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) identifies refugees for resettlement using its established vulnerability criteria. The seven vulnerability criteria used by the UNHCR are Legal and or Physical Protection Needs; Survivors of Torture and/or Violence; Medical Needs; Women and Girls at Risk; Family Reunification; Children and Adolescents at Risk and Lack of Foreseeable Alternative Durable Solutions.</p><p>Persons who are at risk due to their sexual orientation or gender identity are usually referred for resettlement using the category “Legal and Physical Protection Needs”, however they can also be referred under one of the other categories if more applicable. We are working with the UNHCR and other partners to intensify their outreach to groups that might otherwise be reluctant to register for fear of stigma or discrimination and who may be unaware of the options available to them.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-12T12:22:05.153Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650397/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650397/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-02","Refugees: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 1 December (HL3335), and in the light of the inclusion in the vulnerability criteria of persons at risk due to their sexual orientation, how they determine whether people are being accepted into the scheme because of their sexual orientation or gender identity; and how the application of the vulnerability criteria relating to sexual orientation is audited and validated.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650398","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-22","<p>Coroners must by law complete an inquest within six months or as soon as practicable after the death has been reported to them. Inquests may take longer than six months due to the complexity of the case or other factors such as the need to wait for other investigations to finish.</p><p> </p><p>Across the eight coroner jurisdictions in London 1,901 inquests were completed within 6 months and 1,747 inquests were completed in six months or more in 2015.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-12-22T11:52:15.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650398/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650398/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-02","Coroners: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there are delays of six months or more in holding inquests in London, and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Baroness Sharples",,"Baroness Sharples","HL3788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650399","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-14","<p>Overseas electors will register in respect of their last UK address, and will cast their ballot in that constituency. They may choose to vote by postal ballot, in person (if they are in the UK on polling day) or by nominating a proxy to vote on their behalf (postal ballots are not available to overseas electors registered in Northern Ireland).</p><p>Full details are set out in the policy statement published on 7 October 2016 entitled ‘A democracy that works for everyone: British citizens overseas’ which can be found here:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/a-democracy-that-works-for-everyone-british-citizens-overseas" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/a-democracy-that-works-for-everyone-british-citizens-overseas</a></p><p>The franchise for any future referendum would be determined by Parliament in the primary legislation which provides for that referendum.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-12-14T13:11:54.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650399/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650399/answer","overseas_electors_policy_statement.pdf","overseas_electors_policy_statement.pdf","Overseas electors policy statement","Overseas electors policy statement","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650399/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-02","British Nationals Abroad: Voting Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the announcement on 7 October that they intend to remove the 15-year rule on British citizens living overseas voting in parliamentary elections, where, and how, expatriate UK citizens would vote.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL3789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650400","Cabinet Office","false","2017-01-24","<p>The franchise for any future referendum would be determined by Parliament in the primary legislation which provides for that referendum.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-01-24T15:54:22.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650400/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650400/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/650400/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-02","British Nationals Abroad: Voting Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the announcement on 7 October that they intend to remove the 15-year rule on British citizens living overseas voting in parliamentary elections, whether expatriate UK citizens would also be entitled to participate in any future referendums.","false","Biography information for Viscount Waverley",,"Viscount Waverley","HL3790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649373","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-12","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the statement I made to the House on this matter on 31 October 2016, Official Report<em>, </em>Volume 776.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-12-12T15:01:04.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649373/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649373/answer","Nissan_ Sunderland - Hansard Online (P).pdf","Nissan_ Sunderland - Hansard Online (P).pdf","Hansard - Nissan statement","Hansard - Nissan statement","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649373/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-12-01","Business: Government Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of their commitment that any assistance to Nissan would be provided in compliance with state aid and World Trade Organisation rules and kept within current spending limits, whether they will offer similar support to other businesses; and if so, what criteria they will apply in deciding what compensating reductions will be made to ensure that expenditure limits are not breached.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL3736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649374","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-14","<p>Cowley Bridge Junction (on the railway to the immediate north of Exeter) was closed for two days from 21 to 23 November 2016 due to flooding from the Rivers Exe, Culm and Creedy.</p><p> </p><p>Network Rail has already raised all of the lineside railway signal cabinets at the site which put them above the level of the recent flood, significantly reducing train service restitution times after the incident. They advise that more work is planned, including widening and improvement of the existing flood culvert during 2017 and installation of an additional culvert in 2018.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-12-14T12:25:31.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649374/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649374/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","River Exe: Flood Control","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the flooding and railway closures in 2012 and 2016, when they expect the improvements to the River Exe, upstream of Exeter, to be completed.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL3737"
