"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649496","Home Office","false","2016-12-15","<p>Operation BRIDGER is a nationwide police protective security operation to enhance the security of Members of Parliament. This was set up in the wake of a number of threats to MPs’ following the Parliamentary debates on Syria late last year.</p><p>Advice and guidance regarding Members’ security and a process to access funding for standardised security measures was sent to all MPs’ by the Independent Parliamentary Standards Authority (IPSA) on 21 January. Following the murder of Jo Cox, a letter was sent to all Members on 27 June by the Assistant Commissioner Specialist Operations (ACSO), Mark Rowley, and the Chief Executive of IPSA, Marcial Boo, highlighting security measures in place and making some revisions to these, including introducing a police resource to provide for reporting of incidents within the Parliamentary and Diplomatic Protection Command at Westminster.</p><p>On 16 September, the Leader of the House of Commons, David Lidington, and the Chairman of Ways and Means, Lindsay Hoyle, wrote to all Members to outline further changes to the processes for enabling security measures, to highlight police resource and ongoing work to develop a comprehensive picture of risk, and to note the provision of self protection training and protective security advice for Members.</p><p>On 5 December, David Lidington and Lindsay Hoyle provided a further update to Members on personal security arrangements, which included details of a revised process to be followed by Members who have concerns regarding their security.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-12-15T16:28:25.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649496/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649496/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","Members: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 28 November 2016 to Question 52365, when hon. Members were first made aware of Operation Bridger.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","55828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649497","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are responsible for commissioning services to meet the requirements of their population, including obese patients and smokers. In doing so, CCGs need to ensure that the services they provide are fit for purpose, reflect the needs of the local population, and are based on the available evidence and take into account national guidelines.</p><p> </p><p>Major surgery poses much higher risks for severely overweight patients and those who smoke. So local general practitioner-led CCGs are entirely right to ensure these patients first get support to lose weight and try and stop smoking before their operation. Reducing obesity and cutting smoking not only benefits patients but saves the National Health Service and taxpayers millions of pounds.</p><p> </p><p>This does not and cannot mean blanket bans on particular patients, such as smokers, getting operations, which would be inconsistent with the NHS Constitution.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-06T14:23:43.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649497/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649497/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Surgery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department and NHS England plan to take to prevent clinical commissioning groups from rationing treatments by restricting routine surgery for patients who smoke or are clinically obese.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","55790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649498","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>There has been no assessment made directly addressing the effect of the revised Eatwell Guide on milk consumption by children or the effect of the changes on childhood obesity. Government advice continues to encourage consumption of milk and dairy products as part of a healthy, balanced diet for all age groups.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55805","2016-12-07T15:11:57.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649498/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649498/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Milk: Consumption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of the revisions to the Eatwell Guide on levels of milk consumption among children.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","55804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649499","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>We understand that the police investigation into this matter remains on-going.</p><p> </p><p>We are advised that a multi-agency strategic overview board, co-ordinated by the independent chairman of the Derbyshire Safeguarding Children Board, and including the police and local healthcare authorities, meets regularly to review the response to the allegations made in relation to Aston Hall.</p><p> </p><p>The current position remains that timescales for any system-wide Serious Case Review or Learning Review will depend on the outcome of current police enquiries.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-06T14:29:43.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649499/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649499/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Aston Hall Hospital: Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made with the investigation into historical allegations of abuse at Aston Hall, Derbyshire; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","55902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649500","Department of Health","false","2016-12-09","<p>On 29 October 2016 the Department announced the evaluative roll out of non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes. NIPT will be introduced as an additional test into the NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme in England. The evaluative roll out will provide further information to ensure the full national implementation is optimised and safe. This will include, but not be limited to, test turnaround times, numbers of women accepting the offer of screening, impact on invasive procedures, and; information and training materials required.</p><p>Public Health England (PHE), which leads National Health Service Screening Programmes in England, is currently working through the procurement and the evaluative roll out process for NIPT for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes, including the development of tender documents specification and criteria for tendering. The expectation is that laboratories will be contracted to provide NIPT for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes as part of the NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme as part of the evaluative roll out during financial year 2018-19.</p><p>PHE is working through the procurement and the evaluative roll out process for non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes. It is estimated that the test will cost £200-300 per test and PHE has estimated that approximately 10,000 tests will take place per year. The final additional cost or saving will depend on actual uptake rates (i.e. how many women take the test) and on the actual unit costs of tests which NHS England will need to agree with providers.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","55832","2016-12-09T14:57:33.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649500/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649500/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Down's Syndrome: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the annual cost to the NHS of making the non-invasive pre-natal test for Down's syndrome available for all eligible pregnant women in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","55834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649501","Department of Health","false","2016-12-09","<p>On 29 October 2016 the Department announced the evaluative roll out of non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes. NIPT will be introduced as an additional test into the NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme in England. The evaluative roll out will provide further information to ensure the full national implementation is optimised and safe. This will include, but not be limited to, test turnaround times, numbers of women accepting the offer of screening, impact on invasive procedures, and; information and training materials required.</p><p>Public Health England (PHE), which leads National Health Service Screening Programmes in England, is currently working through the procurement and the evaluative roll out process for NIPT for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes, including the development of tender documents specification and criteria for tendering. The expectation is that laboratories will be contracted to provide NIPT for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes as part of the NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme as part of the evaluative roll out during financial year 2018-19.</p><p>PHE is working through the procurement and the evaluative roll out process for non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes. It is estimated that the test will cost £200-300 per test and PHE has estimated that approximately 10,000 tests will take place per year. The final additional cost or saving will depend on actual uptake rates (i.e. how many women take the test) and on the actual unit costs of tests which NHS England will need to agree with providers.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","55834","2016-12-09T14:57:33.203Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649501/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649501/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Down's Syndrome: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to make a formal announcement that the non-invasive pre-natal test for Down's syndrome will be made available for all eligible pregnant women in the UK; and from what date he plans to make that test available to all such women.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","55832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649502","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>There has been no assessment made directly addressing the effect of the revised Eatwell Guide on milk consumption by children or the effect of the changes on childhood obesity. Government advice continues to encourage consumption of milk and dairy products as part of a healthy, balanced diet for all age groups.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55804","2016-12-07T15:11:57.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649502/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649502/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Milk: Consumption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what analysis Public Health England conducted on the potential effect of the changes to the Eatwell Guide's recommendations on milk consumption on obesity in children.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","55805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649504","Department of Health","false","2016-12-09","<p>The NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme offers Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndrome screening to all pregnant women in England. A range of e-learning training materials, for healthcare professionals on fetal anomaly screening, are available on the GOV.UK website at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/fetal-anomaly-screening-programme-overview#training" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/guidance/fetal-anomaly-screening-programme-overview#training</a></p><p> </p><p>On 29 October 2016 the Department announced the evaluative roll out of non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) for Down’s, Edwards’ and Patau’s syndromes. NIPT will be introduced as an additional test into the NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme in England. Public Health England, who lead the NHS Screening Programmes, is working with a range of stakeholders including Antenatal Results and Choices, the Down’s Syndrome Association, Support Organisation for Trisomy 13/18 and the Down Syndrome Research Foundation to develop information and training materials for healthcare professionals and information for prospective parents in preparation for the roll out of NIPT as an additional option in the NHS Fetal Anomaly Screening Programme in England.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-09T10:24:52.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649504/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649504/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Down's Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that health professionals have training on providing positive information and advice to pregnant women who are expecting a child with Down's syndrome.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","55833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649505","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Nuffield Council on Bioethics plans to publish the findings of its project on non-invasive prenatal testing in March 2017.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T10:25:36.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649505/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649505/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649505/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Down's Syndrome: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the timetable is for the Nuffield Council for BioEthics to report to his Department on the non-invasive pre-natal test for Down's syndrome.","false","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","55835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649506","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>Cyber Security, including cyber crime, is a top priority threat to national security. Through the National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP), we invested over £90 million under the last Parliament to bolster the law enforcement response, and we are continuing to invest. This Government has committed to transformative investment of £1.9 billion on cyber security over the next five years, including for tackling cyber crime. This year we have published a second five-year National Cyber Security Strategy and established the National Cyber Security Centre which will act as a ‘one stop shop’ for national cyber security.</p><p>Action Fraud, the national reporting point for fraud and financially-motivated cyber crime, has guidance on its website about Romance Fraud, which can be found at: http://www.actionfraud.police.uk/fraud-az-romance-scams The Government expects social media companies and internet platforms to have robust processes in place and to act promptly when abuse is reported. The Government continues to work closely with social media companies and other relevant actors and experts to make sure they are committed to protecting those who use their platforms.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-12-12T16:36:03.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649506/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649506/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","Sexual Offences: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to tackle crimes connected with the use of dating apps.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","55836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649507","Department of Health","false","2016-12-09","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish (Andrew Gwynne) on 7 December 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-11-30/55662/" target="_blank">55662</a>.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-09T14:38:33.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649507/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649507/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-12-01","Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department takes to monitor the performance of NHS ambulance trusts.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","55837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649508","Home Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>We expect social media companies, and internet platforms, to have robust processes in place and to act promptly when abuse is reported. The Government continues to work closely with social media companies and other relevant actors and experts to make sure they are committed to protecting those who use their platforms.</p><p>The law is clear that what is illegal offline is illegal online. Robust legislation is in place to deal with internet trolls, cyber-stalking and harassment, and perpetrators of grossly offensive, obscene or menacing behaviour.</p><p>The Criminal Justice Act 2015 strengthened two existing communications offences: section 1 of the Malicious Communications Act 1988, and section 127 of the Communications Act 2003 which can now be used to prosecute misuse of social media. The police now have longer to investigate either offence, and the maximum penalty for the former has been increased to two years imprisonment.</p><p>The Crown Prosecution Service published guidance to prosecutors in October on crimes involving social media. The Home Office has allocated £4.6 million of the Police Transformation Fund specifically to begin the critical work of setting up a comprehensive and joined up programme of digital transformation across policing.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-12-07T16:40:54.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649508/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649508/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","Social Media: Bullying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to tackle online abuse and harassment on social media networks.","false","Biography information for Stewart Malcolm McDonald","Glasgow South","Stewart Malcolm McDonald","55847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649509","Home Office","false","2016-12-21","<p>We have worked closely with the French authorities to support the clearance of the Calais camp and to transfer children eligible to come to the UK. Since 10 October, we have transferred over 750 children from France. The current phase has been concluded. More children will be transferred from across Europe under the Immigration Act in the coming months, including children from France.</p><p>We will continue to meet our obligation under the Dublin Regulation to transfer unaccompanied refugee children to the UK where a family link has been established.</p><p>In line with the legislation, we will in due course specify the number of unaccompanied refugee children to be transferred to the UK under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-21T11:06:14.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649509/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649509/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649509/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if the Government will make it its policy to transfer 1,000 children from Calais to the UK before Christmas 2016.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","55864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649510","Home Office","false","2016-12-20","<p>127 EEA nationals were removed from the UK under Operation Adoze.</p><p>Notes:</p><p>1 Operation Adoze figures represent encounters of EEA nationals between 1 November 2015 and 31 December 2015.</p><p>2 Returns figures include those returned after the initial encounter and up to 30 September 2016, in line with published statistics.</p><p>3 These statistics have been taken from a live operational database. As such, numbers may change as information on that system is updated.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-20T14:26:47.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649510/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649510/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","EEA Nationals: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been removed from the UK under Operation Adoze since its introduction; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","55899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649511","Home Office","false","2016-12-12","<p>Operation Temperer is a national contingency plan announced as part of the Strategic Defence and Security Review on 23 November 2015 by the, then, Prime Minster, David Cameron. It enables the police to draw on large scale military support in response to a significant terrorist incident. If the need to activate the Operation should arise then Government would meet the associated costs.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-12-12T16:36:52.51Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649511/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649511/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","Counter-terrorism: South Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what financial resources the Government committed to support the (a) civilian and (b) military components of Operation Temperer in each of the last two years in the South Wales police force area.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","55876"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649513","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>The UK will, in due course, be leaving the EU but the importance of law enforcement co-operation with our EU and global allies has not changed.</p><p>We are exploring options for cooperation arrangements once the UK has left the EU. We will do what is necessary to keep people safe, but it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions on specific measures in advance of negotiations.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-08T16:12:41.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649513/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649513/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","EU Common Foreign and Security Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to co-operate on knowledge-sharing related to policy and security with other EU countries after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","55798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649514","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Seasonal Agricultural Workers Scheme was closed at the end of 2013 when the transitional employment restrictions applied to nationals of Bulgaria and Romania were lifted. Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. The agricultural sector will until then continue to be able to recruit EU-national workers to meet their labour needs until the UK leaves the EU.</p><p>There are a number of options as to how EU migration might work once we have left. We are about to begin these negotiations and it would be wrong to set out further positions in advance. At every step of these negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-08T16:15:27.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649514/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649514/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649514/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","Agriculture: Seasonal Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the agricultural workers scheme.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","55796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649515","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Home Office is committed to publishing data in an orderly way as part of the regular quarterly Immigration Statistics, in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics. Latest statistics published on 01 December confirmed that a total of 4,414 Syrians have been resettled under the scheme since it began, 4,162 of these arriving in the 12 months to the end of September 2016.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-08T16:15:07.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649515/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649515/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-12-01","Refugees: Syria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many refugees have resettled in the UK under the Vulnerable Persons Resettlement Scheme in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","55879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649516","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-08","<p>The UK Government has committed to help 60 million people to gain access to water and sanitation by 2020. The focus will be to deliver results with best value for money, rather than pre-set budget allocations.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-08T16:49:50.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649516/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649516/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649516/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-01","Developing Countries: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has assessed the potential merits of increasing the proportion of its overseas development aid dedicated to water, sanitation and hygiene.","false","Biography information for Derek Thomas","St Ives","Derek Thomas","55919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649517","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Secretary of State is conducting a full examination of DFID’s programme in the Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPTs). The outcomes of the examination will be reflected in our published description of the DFID country programme in due course.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-12-06T15:19:25.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649517/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649517/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-12-01","Palestinians: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether and when her Department plans to publish its review of aid to the Occupied Palestinian Territories separately to its Bilateral Aid Review.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","55929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649518","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Conflict, Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) has a budget of £1.1billion, due to grow to £1.34billion by the end of 2019/20. As reflected in the Strategic Defence and Security Review (SDSR), the additional c.£200m will increase Government’s capacity to prevent threats and build stability, as well as respond to crises more quickly and effectively. The CSSF will have more resources and expertise to address the drivers of transnational threats to stability such as extremism, illegal migration and serious and organised crime.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-12-06T09:56:01.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649518/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649518/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649518/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-12-01","Conflict, Stability and Security Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to page 20 of his Department's report, entitled Rising to the challenge of ending poverty: the Bilateral Development Review 2016, published in December 2016, how the Government plans to expand the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","55939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649519","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government is committed to commencing section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 and will do so as soon as possible.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2016-12-06T17:58:29.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649519/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649519/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649519/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-01","Serious Crime Act 2015","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on what date she plans for the commencement of section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","55928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649520","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-22","<p>Sexual communication with a child is abhorrent, which is why the government legislated to make it a specific offence. We remain committed to commencing this law as soon as possible.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-12-22T01:51:32.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649520/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649520/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649520/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-01","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government plans to issue a commencement order for the provisions in the Serious Crime Act 2015 relating to sexual communications with a child.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","55926"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649521","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-06","<p>All new Prison Officers receive Mental Health Awareness training as part of their Prison Officer Entry Level Training (POELT). All establishments provide mental health training for Prison Officers. The ‘Introduction to Mental Health’ course and ‘Introduction to Safer Custody’ course are delivered locally for all operational Prison Officers Band 3, 4 and 5.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-06T17:24:15.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649521/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649521/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-01","Prison Officers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of operational prisoner officers at each band have received mental health awareness training; what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of that training in reducing self-harm and suicides in prisons; and if she will make it her policy to ensure that all operational prison officers receive that training.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","55907"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649522","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-15","<p>As the Government made clear in the recent consultation on court reform, we are considering what further changes are needed to the family justice system and will bring forward proposals in due course.</p><p> </p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2016-12-15T17:19:14.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649522/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649522/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-01","Divorce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans she has to allow separating couples to divorce without blame.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","55785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649523","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-14","<p>Divorce law enables a court to end a marriage which has irretrievably broken down, where one party to the marriage petitions for a divorce. A number of tools and services, such as the online Parenting Plan, are available to help divorcing parents reach agreements about the needs of their children, for example covering questions about living arrangements and education. If there is a dispute, parents can choose to use mediation which can be quicker, less stressful for families and cheaper than litigation.</p><p> </p><p>Where agreement is not possible, either parent can apply to the court for an order to determine with whom the child is to live or spend time, but is required first to attend a meeting to consider mediation. If the case goes before the court, the court is legally required to make the child’s welfare its paramount concern in any decision regarding the child’s future, while recognising the importance of parental involvement.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-14T17:09:45.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649523/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649523/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-01","Divorce","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment she has made of the efficacy of divorce law in helping divorcing parents put the needs of their children first.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","55786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649524","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>Those who break our laws should be removed from the country at the earliest opportunity. In 2015/16, we removed 5,810 Foreign National Offenders (FNOs) from prisons, immigration removal centres and the community, the highest number ever. Over 33,000 FNOs have been removed since 2010.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-03T14:21:53.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649524/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649524/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-12-01","Offenders: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress the Government has made in returning foreign nationals to their own countries after they have completed a prison term in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","55830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649525","Scotland Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>Further to my answer of 30 November on this issue, the UK Government has made clear that it is willing to work with those affected on options for addressing unrestored opencast mines in Scotland. Environmental liabilities are a devolved matter and the Scottish Government has lead responsibility on funding provision for these matters.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2016-12-06T12:14:49.76Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649525/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649525/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649525/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2016-12-01","Opencast Mining: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2016 to Question 54983, for what reasons he has not provided information on funding from the public purse on enabling open cast restoration works to be undertaken within (a) Scotland and (b) East Ayrshire; what future funding provision the Government has for enabling such works; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","55829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649526","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-06","<p>The independent review of the HS2 Ltd tunnel costings relating to HS2 Colne Valley viaduct, which was commissioned by the Secretary of State for Transport, was conducted by the Department for Transport’s lead non-executive director, Ed Smith CBE, FCA, CPFA, Hon DUniv, Hon LLDs.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of the independent review report, which is entitled ‘Independent Review of HS2 Ltd Cost Estimates contained in the Hillingdon Working Group Report’, has been placed in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-12-06T11:54:56.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649526/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649526/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish an independent review of tunnel costings relating to High Speed 2 (HS2) and the Colne Valley viaduct that was provided by the promoter to the House of Lords HS2 Select Committee; and what the name of the organisations and qualifications of those conducting that independent review were.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","55822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649527","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-15","<p>The Franchise Agreement specifies the minimum requirements for train operators to conduct public consultations on significant alterations to train services (which can be additions or reductions). These are usually aligned to timetable change dates in May and December each year and are associated with major changes to the Timetable, with length of consultation related to the nature of the complexity of any proposed changes. Major proposed changes to the permanent train service specification (and associated timetable) require longer periods for consultation with stakeholders (usually at least 12 weeks) and must include bodies statutorily defined within the Railways Act 2005, such as Transport Focus.</p><p> </p><p>Temporary, short-term changes to the timetable, due to restrictions of use imposed by the need of Network Rail to undertake engineering work (planned and unplanned) to the rail network, are not subject to consultation requirements. However, the Franchise Agreement specifies requirements upon train operating companies to advise passengers of amended timetable information well in advance to enable them to plan their journeys accordingly.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-12-15T14:06:41.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649527/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649527/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","Railways: Public Consultation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what mandatory requirements his Department places on train operating companies to conduct public consultations on reductions to services.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","55872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649528","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>The government published net present values (NPVs) for all three of the airport expansion options in Chapter 7 of the Further Review and Sensitivities Report.</p><p> </p><p>The NPV is an important metric in the economic analysis, but does not capture all relevant evidence, for example other quantified impacts that are not included, such as the local jobs created and trade benefits, and non-monetised impacts. The economic analysis is part of a wider evidence base, which includes the consideration of commercial, financial, deliverability and strategic issues. Further information can be found in the Airport Commission’s Final Report.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-07T15:41:37.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649528/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649528/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","London Airports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment the Government made of the relative net present values of the potential expansion of Gatwick and Heathrow Airports when making its decision on airport expansion in the South East.","false","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond","55865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649529","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-15","<p>As the CrossCountry franchise has recently been awarded, officials are not in negotiation with CrossCountry about renewing the franchise for the Manchester to Birmingham to Devon route.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-12-15T13:56:30.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649529/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649529/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649529/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","Cross Country Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether officials of his Department are in negotiations with Arriva-CrossCountry Trains on renewing that company's franchise on the Manchester to Birmingham to Devon route.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","55873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649530","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-15","<p>The CrossCountry Direct Award commenced on 16 October 2016 and expires on 13 October 2019. The Manchester to Birmingham to Devon route would then be considered as part of the next franchise.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-12-15T13:51:37.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649530/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649530/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649530/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","Cross Country Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Arriva-CrossCountry Trains franchise agreement for the Manchester to Birmingham to Devon route ends.","false","Biography information for Kevin Foster","Torbay","Kevin Foster","55874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649531","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-08","<p>The legislation that provides for licensing of taxi and private hire vehicle services is enabling in its nature, giving local licensing authorities the discretion to set standards that they deem to be appropriate for their area. Local licensing authorities can already require the installation of CCTV in all taxis and private hire vehicles (PHVs) and a number already do so.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s position on recommending the installation of CCTV in taxis and PHVs is being reviewed as part of the drafting of Statutory Guidance to safeguard children and vulnerable adults when using these vehicles. The Government will consult on this early next year.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-12-08T17:03:04.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649531/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649531/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649531/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","Taxis: CCTV","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of requiring private hire vehicles to install CCTV cameras for the purpose of enhancing driver and passenger safety.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","55923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649532","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-06","<p>Our current assumption is that up to two high speed trains an hour, to and from London, would be able to serve Sheffield station without the need for extra capacity, if the proposals on which we are currently consulting for the HS2 route in South Yorkshire are confirmed. We are also investigating routing up to two further HS2 services from Birmingham to Leeds through Sheffield. This would require an additional northern junction which is also covered in the current consultation.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-12-06T11:45:58.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649532/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649532/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649532/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-12-01","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Sheffield Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of High Speed 2 (HS2) trains that could be timetabled each hour during the day if Sheffield city centre station is chosen for HS2 operating at its current capacity; and whether his Department plans to increase capacity at that station.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","55936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649533","Wales Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>I have regular meetings with the Secretary of State for the Department for Exiting the European Union, as well as attending the Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations. My Department is working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union to ensure we get the best possible deal for Wales and the UK as a whole. Recently I welcomed the Secretary of State to Wales where we attended the CBI Wales Annual dinner and visited SPTS Technologies in Newport.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-12-06T17:35:49.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649533/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649533/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649533/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-12-01","UK Trade with EU: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for leaving the European Union on the (a) value to Wales of access to the single market and (b) financial cost of paying to maintain that access after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","55849"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649534","Wales Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>I recognise many businesses in Wales trade with the single market and my Department is working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union to ensure we get the best possible deal for Wales and the UK as a whole.</p><p> </p><p>Leaving the EU will lead to new opportunities for businesses in Wales as we build on our strengths as an open, dynamic, trading nation.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-12-06T17:32:04.37Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649534/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649534/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649534/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-12-01","UK Trade with EU: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what estimate he has made of the economic value to Wales of the UK's membership of the single market.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","55855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649535","Wales Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>We have worked closely with the Welsh Government to ensure fair and transparent funding and, as far as possible, to develop a system for administering the levy which complements the skills and apprenticeship policies of each of the devolved administrations.</p><p> </p><p>Last month, HM Treasury announced that £128m will be allocated to Wales in the first year of the levy alone. It is up to the Welsh Government to decide what proportion of this is allocated to funding apprenticeships and skills policy.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-12-06T17:29:44.95Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649535/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649535/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649535/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-12-01","Apprentices: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what representations he has received from the Welsh Government on the effect of the apprenticeship levy on Wales.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","55889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649536","Wales Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>There has been a long standing commitment that Wales will get its fair share from this levy. Last month, HM Treasury announced that £128m, £133m and £138m will be allocated to Wales in the first, second and third years of the levy respectively. On top of this, the UK Government has committed additional funding for Wales of £13.7m in the first and £6.2m in the second year to ensure that Wales receives its fair share of any under spend that occurs in the adjustment period.</p><p> </p><p>Skills policy is a devolved matter in Wales, and therefore it is up to the Welsh Government to decide what proportion of this funding is allocated to apprenticeships and skills policy.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-12-06T17:34:02.913Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649536/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649536/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649536/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-12-01","Apprentices: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the effect of the apprenticeship levy on Wales.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","55890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649537","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-06","<p>We have committed to a review of the Gender Recognition Act to streamline and demedicalise the gender recognition process, which will include an examination of how alternative gender recognition schemes operate in other countries.</p><p>We have begun our programme of work on reviewing the gender recognition process, and we will provide an update on the Government’s progress in 2017.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","55808","2016-12-06T15:18:16.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649537/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649537/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649537/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-01","Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, with reference to the Government's response to Recommendations 4 to 8 of Women and Equalities Committee Report on Transgender Equality, Cm 9301, if she will set out a timetable for the review of the Gender Recognition Act to determine whether changes can be made to improve it in order to streamline and de-medicalise the gender recognition process; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","55809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649538","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-06","<p>We have committed to a review of the Gender Recognition Act to streamline and demedicalise the gender recognition process, which will include an examination of how alternative gender recognition schemes operate in other countries.</p><p>We have begun our programme of work on reviewing the gender recognition process, and we will provide an update on the Government’s progress in 2017.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","55809","2016-12-06T15:18:16.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649538/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649538/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649538/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-01","Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, with reference to the Government's response to Recommendations 4 to 8 of the Women and Equalities Committee Report on Transgender Equality, Cm 9301, over what timeframe she plans to monitor the implementation of alternative gender recognition processes in other jurisdictions; which such jurisdictions she plans to monitor; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","55808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649539","Women and Equalities","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government regularly engages with transgender organisations to receive feedback and insight into the community. We also listen to testimony and monitor evidence, such as court cases and reports, to improve our understanding and insight.</p><p>This is part of our commitment to understand the needs of the transgender community, in order to tackle the discrimination and inequality they face.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-12-06T15:19:29.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649539/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649539/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649539/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-12-01","Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, with reference to the Government's response to Recommendation 10 of the Women and Equalities Committee Report on Transgender Equality, Cm 9301, through what mechanisms she plans to listen to and monitor people's experiences of discrimination, harassment or victimisation; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","55807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649540","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-06T16:46:43.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649540/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649540/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649540/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Child Poverty Unit: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the Answer of 7 November 2016 to Question 51676, on Child Poverty Unit: staff, if he will give a breakdown of the staff numbers provided by civil service pay grade in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","55841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649541","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Welfare Reform and Work Act 2016 has frozen the majority of working-age benefits for four tax years, from 2016-17 to 2019-20. These benefit rates will therefore remain the same.</p><p> </p><p>These reforms to working-age benefits are part of the Government’s commitment to incentivise work for those who can in a high-wage, low-tax economy. This includes increasing the National Living Wage to £9 an hour by 2020, cutting income tax for over 30 million people and the roll-out of UC. These reforms are working, with employment at historic high levels.</p><p> </p><p>We are also committed to supporting those who cannot work, and those with additional needs. Our triple lock guarantee has meant that the basic State Pension is now over £1,100 a year higher than in 2010. Benefits for the additional costs of disability, and for carers, are exempt from the benefit freeze and will continue to be up-rated in line with the rise in prices.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-06T14:14:02.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649541/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649541/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649541/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will estimate the effect of the forecasts in the Office for Budget Responsibility's Economic and Fiscal Outlook, November 2016, on his Department's estimates of the financial effect on recipients of working age benefits of the freeze on those benefits.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","55848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649542","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>Terminally ill people claiming Attendance Allowance, Disability Living Allowance, Personal Independence Payment, Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) and Universal Credit (UC) via the fast track procedure rather than the normal assessment process, will be reassessed depending on when it is considered most appropriate for the claimant to have their next contact with the Department.</p><p> </p><p>As announced on 1 October, we will stop requiring people with the most severe, lifetime conditions to be repeatedly assessed for ESA and UC. Over the coming months we will work with our health assessment provider, medical professionals and other stakeholders to develop a set of criteria to switch off re-assessments for people with the most severe health conditions or disabilities.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-12-06T17:26:47.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649542/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649542/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649542/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Social Security Benefits: Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which terminal illnesses will be exempted from the reassessment process for benefits.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","55891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649543","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Prime Minister is clear that tackling poverty, disadvantage, and delivering real social reform, is a priority for this Government.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-06T17:42:24.03Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649543/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649543/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649543/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is the policy of the Government to eliminate child poverty.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","55894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649544","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-07","<p>Ministers have met with officials and a wide range of stakeholders whilst developing the non-consensual sex exception. The Government has also run a public consultation on all the exceptions which closed 27 November 2016. The Government will publish the consultation response in due course.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-07T11:26:20.56Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649544/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649544/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649544/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-12-01","Social Security Benefits: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with which trade unions representing civil servants on what dates his Department has met to discuss its plans to limit tax credit payments to two children and protections for victims of rape whose third or subsequent child was born as a result of rape.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","55878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649545","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>Over this period around 600 people, consisting of direct employees and contractors, have been working on the Universal Credit Programme.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-06T14:09:14.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649545/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649545/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649545/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many full-time equivalent members of staff his Department has employed to work on the design and implementation of universal credit in each year since its introduction.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","55887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649546","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>A number of processes are in place to deal with inaccurate data from employers. DWP and HMRC analysts continually monitor the RTI data received, looking for trends, patterns and causes. Both Departments then work together with employers and partners such as software developers and payroll bureaux to improve the quality of the data. This work supplements the bacs payment validation process.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-06T16:52:58.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649546/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649546/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649546/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Universal Credit: PAYE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department takes steps relating to the PAYE RTI data it receives from HM Revenue and Customs to safeguard universal credit claimants from data error.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","55898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649547","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>This Government is absolutely committed to delivering a country that works for everyone – not just the privileged few. The Prime Minister has been clear that tackling poverty and disadvantage, and delivering real social reform, will be a priority for this Government. Evidence shows that two of the biggest drivers of child poverty are long-term worklessness and low earnings.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit is designed to strengthen incentives for parents to move into and progress in work and evidence shows that under Universal Credit claimants move into work significantly faster and stay in work longer than under the old system. In addition, Universal Credit now provides for 85% of childcare costs giving parents the opportunity to work and earn more, so they can support their families and improve the life chances of their children. We have also announced a 2% reduction in the Universal Credit single taper meaning more support for hardworking families.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-06T14:35:17.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649547/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649547/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649547/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessments his Department has made of the potential effect of reductions to universal credit on the number of children in (a) relative and (b) absolute child poverty in each year to 2020.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","55851"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649548","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>This information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-06T16:42:58.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649548/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649548/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649548/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Department for Work and Pensions: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times paperwork related to complaints to his Department have been lost in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","55852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649549","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-07","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-07T12:36:08.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649549/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649549/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649549/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Means-tested Benefits: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who have had their (a) jobseeker's allowance or (b) employment and support allowance payments sanctioned have received hardship payments in Preston constituency since 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","55791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649550","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-07","<p>This information is not currently available. We are considering our strategy for future publications of hardship statistics alongside our routine prioritisation of our statistical work programme.</p><p> </p><p>We have information available about our strategy for the release of Universal Credit statistics here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-statistics-background-information/universal-credit-statistics-background-information" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/universal-credit-statistics-background-information/universal-credit-statistics-background-information</a></p><p> </p><p>The sanctions publication strategy which details the approach being taken by DWP statisticians to improve the sanctions statistics being developed, which include the addition of Universal Credit sanction statistics, can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/benefit-sanction-statistics-publication-strategy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/benefit-sanction-statistics-publication-strategy</a></p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-07T12:40:35.96Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649550/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649550/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649550/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Means-tested Benefits: Preston","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who have had their universal credit payment sanctioned received hardship payments in Preston constituency in each month from 1 January to 31 October 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","55792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649551","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department and our Assessment Providers work with a wide range of organisations representing disabled people, including those who are deaf or have a hearing impairment to make improvements to the service provided. For example, Action on Hearing Loss is a member of the Disability Charities Consortium who I meet with on a regular basis. Recent activity includes strengthening processes for booking British Sign Language interpreters and engagement with the British Deaf Association which has led to a joint review of deaf awareness material for health professionals carrying out assessments.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-12-06T14:26:20.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649551/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649551/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/649551/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-12-01","Social Security Benefits: Hearing Impairment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent representations he has received on the appropriateness of his Department's assessments for hearing impaired people; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Mrs Louise Ellman","55840"
