"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648712","Department for Education","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Department is intending to publish the findings from the Education Funding Agency (EFA) data collection, on asbestos management in schools.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, we published a comprehensive review of asbestos in schools and we are implementing its findings, working with the Health and Safety Executive and others.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","55330 ; 55343 ; 55344 ; 55469 ; 55477 ; 55545","2016-12-08T17:01:09.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648712/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648712/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Schools: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of schools that responded to the Education Funding Agency's 2016 asbestos data collection have a procedure in place detailing control measures required to prevent disturbance of any known asbestos-containing materials.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","55544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648714","Department for Education","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Department is intending to publish the findings from the Education Funding Agency (EFA) data collection, on asbestos management in schools.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, we published a comprehensive review of asbestos in schools and we are implementing its findings, working with the Health and Safety Executive and others.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","55330 ; 55343 ; 55344 ; 55469 ; 55477 ; 55544","2016-12-08T17:01:09.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648714/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648714/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Schools: Asbestos","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of schools that responded to the Education Funding Agency's 2016 asbestos data collection have a process in place to ensure that people who disturb asbestos in a school, including building contractors and those performing activities such as IT installations, receive information on the potential presence of asbestos.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","55545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648715","Department for Education","false","2016-12-06","<p>On 20 October, the department published the Early Years Foundation Stage Profile (EYFSP) results for the 2015 to 2016 academic year at a national and local authority level, which are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2015-to-2016</a>. At a national level, 69.3% of children achieved a good level of development (GLD), which is an increase of 3 percentage points on 2015 (compared to 67.4% in Yorkshire and Humber, which is an increase of 2.8 percentage points on Yorkshire and Humber’s 2015 data).</p><p>Every child deserves the best possible start in life and high-quality early education is key to future outcomes, particularly for disadvantaged children. That is why we are working hard to ensure parents and children - wherever they live in England - have access to high quality early years education places through the funded 15 hour entitlement for disadvantaged two-year-olds and for all three- and four-year-olds. At present, 84% of two-year-olds are taking up their entitlement in a good or outstanding setting (compared with 86% in Yorkshire and Humber) and 86% of all three- and four-years-olds take up their entitlement in a good or outstanding setting (compared to 83% in Yorkshire and Humber). The Early Years Pupil Premium provides over £300 per eligible child to improve outcomes for disadvantaged children and, from September 2017, working parents who meet the eligibility criteria will also have access to an additional 15 hours of funded early education.</p><p>Our early years funding formula includes an additional needs factor – to better target funding towards local authorities with a higher relative proportion of children with additional needs – and an area cost adjustment to reflect the different costs of providing childcare in different areas of the country. This will help to ensure that all children can access quality early education in their area.</p><p>The government is taking further steps to understand the regional attainment gap. In May 2016, the department commissioned a feasibility study to investigate the regional gap in early years at age 5, which made recommendations to undertake a further study through longitudinal analysis of the Millennium Cohort Study (MSC) to assess variation in attainment and evaluate the potential drivers of a regional gap. Acting on the feasibility report, the department has commissioned a study to build on the recommendations of the feasibility report, which will be able to help unpick the potential drivers on the regional attainment gap.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","55593","2016-12-06T14:57:07.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648715/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648715/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Pre-school Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to reduce the difference in attainment between children under five years old from different socio-economic groups.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","55594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648716","Department for Education","false","2016-12-06","<p>On 20 October, the department published the Early Years Foundation Stage Profile (EYFSP) results for the 2015 to 2016 academic year at a national and local authority level, which are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/early-years-foundation-stage-profile-results-2015-to-2016</a>. At a national level, 69.3% of children achieved a good level of development (GLD), which is an increase of 3 percentage points on 2015 (compared to 67.4% in Yorkshire and Humber, which is an increase of 2.8 percentage points on Yorkshire and Humber’s 2015 data).</p><p>Every child deserves the best possible start in life and high-quality early education is key to future outcomes, particularly for disadvantaged children. That is why we are working hard to ensure parents and children - wherever they live in England - have access to high quality early years education places through the funded 15 hour entitlement for disadvantaged two-year-olds and for all three- and four-year-olds. At present, 84% of two-year-olds are taking up their entitlement in a good or outstanding setting (compared with 86% in Yorkshire and Humber) and 86% of all three- and four-years-olds take up their entitlement in a good or outstanding setting (compared to 83% in Yorkshire and Humber). The Early Years Pupil Premium provides over £300 per eligible child to improve outcomes for disadvantaged children and, from September 2017, working parents who meet the eligibility criteria will also have access to an additional 15 hours of funded early education.</p><p>Our early years funding formula includes an additional needs factor – to better target funding towards local authorities with a higher relative proportion of children with additional needs – and an area cost adjustment to reflect the different costs of providing childcare in different areas of the country. This will help to ensure that all children can access quality early education in their area.</p><p>The government is taking further steps to understand the regional attainment gap. In May 2016, the department commissioned a feasibility study to investigate the regional gap in early years at age 5, which made recommendations to undertake a further study through longitudinal analysis of the Millennium Cohort Study (MSC) to assess variation in attainment and evaluate the potential drivers of a regional gap. Acting on the feasibility report, the department has commissioned a study to build on the recommendations of the feasibility report, which will be able to help unpick the potential drivers on the regional attainment gap.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","55594","2016-12-06T14:57:07.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648716/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648716/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Pre-school Education: Yorkshire and the Humber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to reduce the difference in attainment between children under five years old in Yorkshire and the Humber and the national average for such attainment.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","55593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648717","Department for Education","false","2016-12-14","<p>Parliamentary question 54622 was answered on 09 December 2016.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-14T17:00:27.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648717/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648717/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Department for Education: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when she plans to answer Question 54622, tabled on 23 November 2016 by the hon. Member for Dudley North.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","55583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648718","Department for Education","false","2016-12-08","<p>We have confirmed that no area will see a reduction in per pupil schools funding in the coming year, and the extra £390 million was added to the schools budget in the last Parliament will remain in the baseline. We will confirm local authorities’ final budgets in December, reflecting the latest pupil numbers from the October census, and we will apply an uplift for high needs funding. As my Rt Hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Education, said at the Education Select Committee in September, we currently do not plan to allocate additional schools funding in 2017-18.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-08T11:43:12.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648718/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648718/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department plans to provide interim funding to schools before the fairer funding formula is introduced in 2018-19.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648719","Department for Education","false","2016-12-08","<p>All schools are required to teach a balanced and broadly based curriculum that promotes the spiritual, moral, cultural, mental and physical development of pupils, and prepares them for the opportunities, responsibilities and experiences of later life. The National Curriculum sets out the subjects and programmes of study which must be taught to children of compulsory school age in maintained schools in England. It serves an important purpose in setting out an example of a knowledge-based, ambitious, academically rigorous education which every child should experience. If autonomous academies or Multi-Academy Trusts wish to deliver the National Curriculum in their schools, they can do so confidently. We want academies to use their freedoms to innovate and build more stretching and tailored curricula, to meet the particular needs of their pupils.</p><p> </p><p>The new National Curriculum, taught from September 2014, focuses on the essential knowledge that pupils should acquire during their time at school so that teachers can design a wider school curriculum that best meets the needs of their pupils. The programmes of study for citizenship set out that teaching should equip pupils with the knowledge to explore political and social issues critically, to weigh evidence, debate and make reasoned arguments. Beyond the prescribed curriculum, schools have the freedom to teach topics, such as current affairs, to ensure that children receive a rounded education.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-12-08T11:40:07.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648719/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648719/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Politics and Government: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what guidance her Department provides to schools on teaching pupils about current affairs within the curriculum.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648720","Department for Education","false","2016-12-08","<p>Bullying, including homophobic, biphobic and transphobic bullying, is unacceptable and should not be tolerated in our schools. The Government is committed to tackling it in all forms.</p><p> </p><p>All schools are required by law to have a behaviour policy with measures to tackle bullying among pupils. Schools are free to develop their own anti-bullying strategies but they are held clearly to account for their effectiveness through Ofsted. We trust schools to decide for themselves what training their staff need in order to be able to do this effectively.</p><p> </p><p>However, we know that individuals who are, or perceived to be, homosexual, bisexual or transgender are disproportionately affected by bullying. In 2015, research by the UCL Institute of Education identified that 56% of young LGB people aged 14-16 were bullied compared to 45% of their heterosexual peers. To help schools to tackle bullying and support victims, in September 2016 the Department for Education and the Government Equalities Office announced £4.4m of funding for 10 projects to tackle bullying, including £2.8 million for projects tackling specifically homophobic, transphobic and biphobic bullying. This programme focuses on primary and secondary schools in England which currently have no, or ineffective, measures in place. The funding will involve voluntary sector organisations engaging with teachers and schools through training, and supporting them to work through a whole school approach. Further information can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/thousands-more-children-to-benefit-from-anti-bullying-app" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/thousands-more-children-to-benefit-from-anti-bullying-app</a>.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-12-08T17:16:27.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648720/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648720/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-30","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent discussions her Department has had with teachers and other education providers on the training required by teachers to effectively tackle homophobic, biphobic and transphobic bullying.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648721","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Government’s THINK! road safety campaign promotes road safety learning amongst children and young people via its online educational resource programme. THINK! have a suite of downloadable materials - tailored by age group - available to teachers, parents and road safety professionals to help them deliver road safety education to pupils.</p><p> </p><p>Included in these resources is practical information and advice for how children can stay safe on our roads during the winter months when the nights are longer.</p><p> </p><p>THINK! is in the process of reviewing the child and teen resource to ensure that the materials are consistent with modern educational approaches.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-12-08T16:49:13.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648721/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648721/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-30","Roads: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to promote the road safety message to pupils, particularly during periods of the year when the UK is not on daylight saving time.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648722","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-08","<p>A summary of the meeting I held on 19 November 2015 with the Sheep Dip Sufferers Support Group is publicly available on its web site:</p><p><a href="http://www.sheepdipsufferers.uk/campaigning/Summary%20of%20meeting.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.sheepdipsufferers.uk/campaigning/Summary%20of%20meeting.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-08T15:30:38.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648722/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648722/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Sheep Dipping: Organophosphates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish the minutes of the meeting in November 2015 between the Sheep Dip Sufferers Support Group and the Minister of State for Agriculture, Fisheries and Food.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","55615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648723","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-08","<p>The 2014 findings of the COT review on the health effects of the exposure to organophosphates is in the public domain and can be found on the COT’s website: <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140909095303/http:/cot.food.gov.uk/cotstatements/cotstatementsyrs/cotstatements2014/cotstatorg" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20140909095303/http:/cot.food.gov.uk/cotstatements/cotstatementsyrs/cotstatements2014/cotstatorg</a>.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-08T15:59:15.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648723/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648723/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Organophosphates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will take steps to publicise better the 2014 findings of the Committee on Toxicity as far as they relate to the health effects of exposure to organophosphates.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","55613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648724","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-08","<p>My hon. Friend will be aware that I met the Sheep Dip Sufferers Support Group about a year ago and discussed this issue in depth. The Committee on Toxicity has looked at this issue exhaustively, examining 26 different studies over a period of more than a decade, and concluded that in the absence of acute poisoning there would not be meaningful long-term effects.</p><p>To the best of my knowledge there is no new scientific evidence available that would alter this conclusion. I am sympathetic to farmers suffering from ill health but at this time I do not feel a further meeting would be beneficial.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-08T15:55:18.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648724/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648724/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Sheep Dipping: Organophosphates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will meet the Sheep Dip Sufferers Support Group to discuss the effects of organophosphates.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","55614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648725","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Veterinary Medicines Directorate (VMD) has recorded the number of reports of suspected adverse reactions in humans to OP dips received each year since records began in 1985. To date this figure is 634. To the best of the VMD’s knowledge this is most comprehensive dataset available.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-08T15:58:17.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648725/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648725/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Sheep Dipping: Organophosphates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will estimate the number of farmers that have reported illnesses relating to exposure to organophosphate sheep dips since 1990.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","55611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648726","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Sheep Scab (Revocation) Order 1992 revoked The Sheep Scab (National Dip) Order 1990, the Sheep Scab (National Dip) (Amendment) Order 1991 and the Sheep Scab Order 1992. This consequently ended the compulsory annual sheep dipping requirement.</p><p> </p><p>The Government released information explaining why the decision was taken to end compulsory dipping, and the conclusions of the VPC reviews of organophosphate sheep dips at the time in May of this year. I sent a letter, explaining this, to the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee and this was copied to Tom Rigby of the Sheep Dip Sufferers Support Group.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-08T11:55:18.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648726/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648726/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Sheep Scab (Revocation) Order 1992","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will publish documents held by her Department relating to the reasons for the introduction of the Sheep Scab (Revocation) Order 1992.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","55612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648727","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-05","<p>Latest compliance data show that the UK is meeting the EU daily and annual mean limits values for particulate matter (PM) concentrations at both PM<sub>10</sub> and PM<sub>2.5</sub> size categories.</p><p>No specific assessment has been made of the potential merits of reducing the limit value for PM from EU limit values to the World Health Organisation air quality guidelines</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-05T11:12:50.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648727/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648727/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of reducing the limit value for particulate matter from 25g/m3 to the World Health Organisation's air quality guidelines of 10g/m3.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","55585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648728","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-05","<p>The assessment criteria used by the Joint Air Quality Unit to allocate funding from the Air Quality Grant are set out in the Invitation to Apply which was provided to all eligible authorities on its launch.</p><p> </p><p>All applications for grant funding are subject to two stages of assessment. Applications are first assessed against six criteria: delivering air quality benefits, strategic alignment, value for money, deliverability, monitoring and evaluation, and knowledge transfer. Applications which pass the first stage are then referred to a Grant board which reviews the projects against further criteria: portfolio delivery against the grant objective, balance between immediate action and strengthening the evidence base, and geographic diversity.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-05T09:32:14.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648728/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648728/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what criteria the Joint Air Quality Unit uses to allocate air quality grant funding.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","55586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648729","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-06","<p>I have recently written to the leaders, chief executives and directors of public health of local authorities with air quality challenges across England, including Calderdale Council, to highlight the need to monitor progress on local improvements in air quality and ensure that the measures they are taking deliver results as soon as possible. I look forward to receiving Calderdale Council’s response.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Local Air Quality Management (LAQM) Review and Assessment process, local authorities are required to submit an Annual Status Report (ASR) to Defra each year. Calderdale Council has consistently met its reporting obligations since 2009.</p><p> </p><p>Calderdale Council’s ASR for 2016 indicates that the Council declared seven Air Quality Management Areas (AQMAs) between 2007 and 2014 due to exceedances of the annual mean nitrogen dioxide objective. These AQMAs are located throughout the borough covering areas surrounding busy road networks.</p><p> </p><p>Defra’s detailed appraisal of the ASR was sent to the Council in August. It set out recommendations to help improve air quality in its area. This included advice that the Council should aim to: revise its action plan published in 2009 as it only covered three of the seven current AQMAs; produce its first Air Quality Strategy, as well as adopting the West Yorkshire Low Emissions Strategy; and make improvements to its reporting of progress on measures and to its air quality monitoring regime. The Council has subsequently indicated that its action plan is under review.</p><p> </p><p>Between 2011 and 2016, the Defra LAQM Helpdesk has provided technical support to Calderdale Council on a range of issues including pollutant monitoring and source apportionment, biomass screening and AQMA administrative support.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","55596","2016-12-06T11:44:03.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648729/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648729/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Air Pollution: Calderdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions her Department has had with Calderdale Council on improving air quality in Calderdale.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","55595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648730","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-06","<p>I have recently written to the leaders, chief executives and directors of public health of local authorities with air quality challenges across England, including Calderdale Council, to highlight the need to monitor progress on local improvements in air quality and ensure that the measures they are taking deliver results as soon as possible. I look forward to receiving Calderdale Council’s response.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the Local Air Quality Management (LAQM) Review and Assessment process, local authorities are required to submit an Annual Status Report (ASR) to Defra each year. Calderdale Council has consistently met its reporting obligations since 2009.</p><p> </p><p>Calderdale Council’s ASR for 2016 indicates that the Council declared seven Air Quality Management Areas (AQMAs) between 2007 and 2014 due to exceedances of the annual mean nitrogen dioxide objective. These AQMAs are located throughout the borough covering areas surrounding busy road networks.</p><p> </p><p>Defra’s detailed appraisal of the ASR was sent to the Council in August. It set out recommendations to help improve air quality in its area. This included advice that the Council should aim to: revise its action plan published in 2009 as it only covered three of the seven current AQMAs; produce its first Air Quality Strategy, as well as adopting the West Yorkshire Low Emissions Strategy; and make improvements to its reporting of progress on measures and to its air quality monitoring regime. The Council has subsequently indicated that its action plan is under review.</p><p> </p><p>Between 2011 and 2016, the Defra LAQM Helpdesk has provided technical support to Calderdale Council on a range of issues including pollutant monitoring and source apportionment, biomass screening and AQMA administrative support.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","55595","2016-12-06T11:44:03.313Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648730/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648730/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648730/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Air Pollution: Calderdale","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions her Department has had with Calderdale Council on reducing the level of pollutants in the air quality management areas within that council's area.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","55596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648731","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-05","<p>Good progress has been made on drafting the various required statutory instruments and guidance, working with the Stakeholder Working Group who developed the recommendations for reform. The group produced a finely balanced package of recommendations and we want to present our work in one go because this is very much a package of recommendations. We hope to bring it forward but I am not in a position to say precisely when.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-05T11:07:03.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648731/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648731/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648731/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Rights of Way","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress has been made on the proposed changes in guidance for public rights of way; and from when she expects the updated version of that guidance will be effective.","false","Biography information for James Morris","Halesowen and Rowley Regis","James Morris","55555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648732","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-05","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Falkirk, John McNally, on 29 November 2016, PQ UIN54298.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-05T11:03:38.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648732/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648732/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648732/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how members of the public will be able to contribute to her Department's forthcoming consultation on the 25 year plan for the environment.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648733","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-05","<p>In interpreting this question, I have assumed the Hon. Member would like to know the two locations which have not yet been repaired to the level prior to the 2015 flooding.</p><p> </p><p>The first location is a culvert in Keighley where work is well-advanced to clear a blockage. The work is expected to be completed by mid-December 2016 and the Environment Agency has a contingency plan to install a temporary sandbag defence should river conditions require it before the works are complete.</p><p> </p><p>The second location is a leaking flood gate in York. The Environment Agency is to seal this gate permanently but the occupier of the land needs to first clear the site. The gate is expected to be sealed by mid-December 2016 but a temporary defence can be quickly installed across the gate if flooding is forecast in the meantime.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-05T11:18:25.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648733/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648733/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648733/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Flood Control: Leeds City Region","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2016 to Question 54932, what the two locations are in Leeds City Region where flood defences have been returned to at least the same standard of protection that existed before the 2015 flooding.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","55724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648734","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-06","<p>The UK supports the management of data-limited stocks on a case-by-case basis, informed by all available evidence including directional trends in fishing mortality, stock biomass and fishing effort. It will be on this basis that Government will consider the Commission’s proposal on fishing opportunities for 2017 for data-limited stocks.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-06T17:29:26.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648734/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648734/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648734/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Total Allowable Catches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if her Department will support European Commission proposals on total allowable catch quotas in 2017 for data-limited stocks at the Fisheries Council meeting in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648735","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>There are, as of 30 November 2016, 3,275 dogs on the Index of Exempted Dogs (dogs that are legally exempt from the general prohibition on certain types of dogs). If the relevant types of dogs were not prohibited the population of these dogs is likely to be higher</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-07T11:37:06.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648735/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648735/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648735/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Dangerous Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 on the population of types of dog prohibited under section 1 of that Act; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648736","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>In 2014, the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 formed part of a wider review into tackling irresponsible ownership of dogs. That review resulted in several changes to the law on dangeorus dogs such as the extension of the offence of allowing a dog to be dangerously out of control to all places and increasing the maximum penalties for such an offence. Early intervention action was also made possible through new measures contained within the Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime &amp; Policing Act 2014, which came into force in 2015. These provisions have supported the minimisation of dog attacks on people.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-07T11:39:20.06Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648736/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648736/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648736/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Dangerous Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 in reducing the number of attacks by dogs on people.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648737","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-06","<p>We are making good progress towards sustainable fishing with more stocks than ever now being fished at Maximum Sustainable Yield (MSY). 31 stocks of the 59 with full analytical assessment in the North East Atlantic (and surrounding waters) were fished in accordance with MSY in 2014, compared with just 19 in 2004[1].</p><p> </p><p>Earlier this year, the UK’s provisional assessment for 2016 indicated that 24 stocks for which the UK has quota will be fished at or below maximum sustainable yield (MSY). A significant majority of these will be fished (a) at MSY rather than (b) below it; information on the specific stocks has been placed in the House Library.</p><p> </p><p>We will be seeking to increase the number of stocks being fished in accordance with MSY in 2017 at the Fisheries Council in December.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] Reports of the Scientific, Technical and Economic Committee for Fisheries (STECF) – Monitoring the performance of the Common Fisheries Policy (STECF-16-05) – CORRIGENDUM to STECF-16-03. 2016. <a href="https://stecf.jrc.ec.europa.eu/documents/43805/55543/2016-03_STECF+16-05+Monitoring+performance+CFP+CORRIGENDUM_JRC100945.pdf" target="_blank">https://stecf.jrc.ec.europa.eu/documents/43805/55543/2016-03_STECF+16-05+Monitoring+performance+CFP+CORRIGENDUM_JRC100945.pdf</a></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-06T17:36:07.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648737/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648737/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648737/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Fishing Catches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many (a) fish stocks and (b) total allowable catches are fished (i) at or below and (ii) above maximum sustainable yield; and what progress her Department has made towards its strategy that all fish stocks are fished at maximum sustainable yield by 2020.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648738","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-06","<p>The International Council for the Exploration of the Sea (ICES) have made significant efforts in recent years to assess stocks where analytical maximum sustainable yield (MSY) assessments and estimates are not available and we support both developing MSY proxies in such cases, as well as moving towards full analytical MSY assessments for any stocks whenever supported by available science and evidence.</p><p> </p><p>When a stock first moves from a data-limited assessment to an analytical MSY assessment, it can result in a large change in the advised Total Allowable Catch (TAC) due to the incorporation of additional evidence such as recruitment, both actual and predicted, rather than reflecting a real change in a stock’s dynamics. Therefore, in some cases it may be appropriate to have a short-term staged transition towards MSY.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-06T17:33:25.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648738/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648738/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648738/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Fishing Catches","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department plans to follow European Commission advice on adopting maximum sustainable yield for fish stock that has improved as a result of the data-limited precautionary approach.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648739","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Government proposes to publish a next steps document shortly which will set out our proposals for the animal establishments licensing review, following analysis of the 1,700 responses to the consultation.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-12-07T12:55:11.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648739/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648739/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648739/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to her Department's consultation on the review of animal establishments licensing in England, which closed on 12 March 2016, when she plans to publish draft regulations on the licensing of animal establishments; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","55734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648740","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-12-06","<p>Natural flood management solutions are an important part of our approach to reducing flood risk. The recently announced £15m investment specifically for natural flood management schemes across England presents an important opportunity to further develop the evidence base around working with natural processes to reduce flood risk. We are, therefore, thinking carefully about where these schemes are based, and so have not yet announced specific locations that will be supported by the fund.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency will be administering the £15m investment, and have already been working with Natural England, Forestry Commission and local partners to identify project proposals. Following the announcement of the fund they can now begin to work with partners to fully scope these opportunities, which will then need to be robustly assessed against a set of agreed criteria. Further details of the process for confirming projects and their locations will be announced in due course.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-12-06T11:46:24.137Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648740/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648740/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648740/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-11-30","Flood Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to her oral contribution of 24 November 2016, Official Report, column 1004 if she will publish a list of projects including their locations that will be supported by the £15 million investment.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","55751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648741","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>There are currently more than 200,000 Internally Displaced People being protected at UN Mission in South Sudan (UNMISS) Protection of Civilians sites across South Sudan. Through our deployment to UNMISS UK troops will provide expertise, particularly in engineering, that will help make those Protection of Civilian sites more secure. Through DFID, we are also providing more than £20 million this financial year to the neighbouring countries of Ethiopia, Uganda and Kenya to help support the more than one million South Sudanese refugees who are seeking refuge there.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-06T11:59:10.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648741/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648741/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648741/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","South Sudan: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken to ensure the safety of refugees in shelters in South Sudan and neighbouring countries.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","55728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648742","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>We recognise the critical role civil society organisations play in South Sudan, both in providing basic support to the population and in developing local level peace-building initiatives which are essential to addressing the longer term impact of the conflict. We work closely with many of these NGOs, sharing information and analysis, and providing support where appropriate.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-06T12:01:51.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648742/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648742/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648742/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","South Sudan: Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with which non-governmental organisations (NGO) and NGO forums in South Sudan his Department has links.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","55729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648743","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-05","<p>In the East of Aleppo city, DFID partners assess that the supply of water is sporadic and the quality inadequate as a result of damage arising from the ongoing Regime offensive. To help address this, DFID implementing partners have supported repairs to water networks and generators and provided water purification tablets and jerry cans. In the West of Aleppo city, where there has been less damage to the water system, supply is assessed as adequate.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-12-05T18:08:04.183Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648743/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648743/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648743/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-30","Syria: Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the level of access for civilians in the city of Aleppo to clean water; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","55776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648744","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>​The Foreign Secretary has discussed our deep concerns about the appalling humanitarian situation with Secretary Kerry and other key partners on a regular basis, including when he hosted a meeting in London on 16 October. The Prime Minister discussed the situation in Aleppo with the leaders of the US, Germany, Italy, France, Spain when she attended a summit in Berlin on 18 November. The Foreign Secretary asked the Russian Foreign Minister on 22 November to use his influence with the Syrian regime to let aid into Aleppo. Our Ambassador to the United Nations has repeated these message in the UN, most recently during the UK and French called emergency session of the Security Council on 30 November. The opposition have agreed the UN's four point plan for Aleppo. The regime needs to also. They could do this in a moment.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-05T14:24:31.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648744/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648744/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648744/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","Syria: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his international counterparts on coordinating the delivery of aid to the city of Aleppo; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","55778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648745","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>We are aware of allegations about the ethnic cleansing of the Rohingya in Burma. Though the lack of access makes facts hard to verify, we are deeply concerned by reports of human rights violations in Rakhine State. I have lobbied the Burmese Government for an investigation into allegations of human rights abuses, as has the Minister of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my noble Friend, the Rt Hon. Baroness Anelay of St Johns, when she visited from 9-12 November. The Government of Burma has committed to an independent investigation and we urge them to make rapid progress with this. We will continue to monitor the situation closely.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-08T16:25:16.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648745/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648745/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648745/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has received on whether ethnic cleansing is taking place against the Rohingya in Burma.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","55755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648746","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>​It is difficult to obtain precise figures about casualties in Syria. In a stark demonstration of the extent of the tragedy, the UN ceased issuing casualty figures in 2014. UN Special Envoy for Syria, Staffan de Mistura estimated in April 2016 that 400,000 people had been killed in the conflict. The Syrian Network for Human Rights reported that 203,000 civilians had been killed between March 2011 and November 2016 and that 92% of them were victims of the Asad regime.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-05T14:20:29.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648746/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648746/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648746/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what his Department's most recent estimate is of the number of civilian casualties across Syria since the conflict began; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","55777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648747","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>In the last month, the Foreign Secretary has met the Prime Ministers of Serbia, Kosovo and Albania, as well as the Chair of the BiH Presidency, in order to support security and political stability in the region.</p><p>The announcement that we will host the 2018 Western Balkans Summit, our senior bilateral contacts, and our engagement through our Embassies and programme funds, all support this Government's commitment to drive forward reform and embed stability in the Western Balkans.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2016-12-08T16:33:33.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648747/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648747/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648747/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","Balkans: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what diplomatic steps his Department is taking to support security and political stability in the Balkan states.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648748","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>​The British Government is deeply concerned by the reports of mass killings in Beni. We are supporting efforts to investigate these horrific incidents, including through funding an independent researcher to assist the UN peacekeeping mission in eastern Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) (MONUSCO) in understanding the underlying drivers of such killings. The UK strongly supports the work of MONUSCO as it seeks to defeat armed groups in DRC. During my visit to the DRC in August, I raised the ongoing violence in eastern DRC with Maman Sidikou, Head of the UN Peacekeeping Mission in eastern DRC (MONUSCO). In mid-November, my colleague, the Parliamentary Undersecretary of State for International Development, James Wharton MP, raised protection of civilians with the UN Deputy Special Representative for Operations and the Rule of Law, David Gressly.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-12-07T15:13:04.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648748/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648748/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648748/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","Democratic Republic of Congo: Homicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to support investigations into the recent killings of communities in Beni and the North Kivu region of the Democratic Republic of Congo.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","55524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648749","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-12-06","<p>The UK continues to assist Iraq in defeating Daesh. We have over 550 personnel in Iraq, assisting with training as part of the Global Coalition's Building Partner Capacity Programme. UK forces have helped to train over 30,000 Iraqi security forces personnel, including over 7,000 Kurdish Peshmerga. The RAF also continues to support the Coalition through participation in airstrikes. At the Warsaw Summit in July 2016, the UK pledged £1 million to help NATO shape its in-country training and capacity building initiative; this money will enable NATO training to start in January 2017.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-12-06T14:06:55.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648749/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648749/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648749/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-11-30","Iraq: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what additional in-country assistance the Government has disbursed to Iraq since the Warsaw NATO Summit in July 2016.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","55568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648751","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>The UK remains firmly opposed to the death penalty in all circumstances. Abolitionist work is high on the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) agenda and is part of the day-to-day work of all diplomatic missions to countries that retain the death penalty. The FCO Human Rights and Democracy Report 2015 makes clear our views on the death penalty and the resumption of executions in Pakistan.</p><p>During his visit to Pakistan in November, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), raised our human rights concerns and the importance we attach to upholding the rule of law. We continue to raise our concerns about the death penalty with the government of Pakistan and urge compliance with its international obligations.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2016-12-05T15:08:25.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648751/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648751/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648751/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-30","Pakistan: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he raised the issue of the death penalty and executions of mentally ill prisoners and those arrested for non-violent drug offences on his recent trip to Pakistan.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","55781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648752","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>Local authorities (LA) have access to the National Child Measurement Programme and NHS Health Checks to identify, monitor and help inform the needs of their local child and adult populations. Public Health England (PHE) will continue to work with LAs on public health approaches that support evidence based and place-based approaches, including the Sustainability Transformation Plans, whilst delivering the actions outlined in the Government's Childhood Obesity Plan.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities continue to invest in a breadth of approaches to tackle obesity, including work to improve the local food offer in public places; create healthier built environments; and provide weight management services to children and adults looking to achieve a healthier weight.</p><p> </p><p>PHE are supporting local authorities to implement effective strategies by developing accessible resources and toolkits that support local authorities to take a place-based and whole systems approach to tackling obesity.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-08T15:50:17.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648752/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648752/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648752/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Obesity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of strategies local authorities have in place to tackle (a) childhood and (b) adult obesity.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","55602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648753","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>The information requested is not held by the Department or the Nursing and Midwifery Council.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-08T10:50:37.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648753/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648753/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648753/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many professionals have been registered on the Nursing and Midwifery Council's nursing register for the Yorkshire North and East and Northern Lincolnshire region in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648754","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>Health Education England (HEE) was established in June 2012 as a special health authority and took on its operational functions from April 2013. The table below shows the total number of full time equivalent pre-registration training places that were funded by HEE in each year from 2013/14 to 2015/16.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>HEE funded training places</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Medical and dental</p></td><td><p>36,139</p></td><td><p>34,189</p></td><td><p>33,365</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-medical</p></td><td><p>78,842</p></td><td><p>91,963</p></td><td><p>92,660</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Health Education England</p><p> </p><p>The table below shows the total number of clinical placements funded by HEE in 2014/15 and 2015/16. The figures relating to the number of clinical placements funded by HEE in 2013/14 is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Clinical placement population</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Medical and dental</p></td><td><p>22,102</p></td><td><p>22,684</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-Medical</p></td><td><p>50,699</p></td><td><p>44,415</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Health Education England</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T15:10:41.777Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648754/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648754/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648754/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many (a) training places and (b) clinical placements have been funded by Health Education England in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648755","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>Health Education England (HEE) was established in June 2012 as a special health authority and took on its operational functions from April 2013. The table below shows the amount spent annually by HEE on funding training places for pre-registration students from 2013/14 to 2015/16. This includes expenditure on tuition, clinical placements and salary support.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>HEE Funding for training places</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2015/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Medical and dental</p></td><td><p>£880 million</p></td><td><p>£882 million</p></td><td><p>£880 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-medical</p></td><td><p>£1,571 million</p></td><td><p>£1,602 million</p></td><td><p>£1,618 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Health Education England</p><p>The table below shows the number of full time equivalent pre-registration training places funded by HEE at Hull and East Yorkshire Trust, Yorkshire Ambulance Trust and Humber NHS Foundation Trust from 2013/14 to 2015/16.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>HEE funded training places</p></td><td><p>Hull and East Yorks</p></td><td><p>Yorks Ambulance</p></td><td><p>Humber</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>Medical and Dental</p></td><td><p>138.5</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>5.9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-medical</p></td><td><p>267.1</p></td><td><p>121</p></td><td><p>100.7</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>Medical and Dental</p></td><td><p>135.9</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>5.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-medical</p></td><td><p>254.6</p></td><td><p>49</p></td><td><p>86.7</p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="2"><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>Medical and Dental</p></td><td><p>123.2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-medical</p></td><td><p>256</p></td><td><p>76</p></td><td><p>95.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Health Education England</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T15:06:45.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648755/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648755/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648755/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much Health Education England has spent on funding training places in each year since 2009; and how many of those training places were provided in the (a) Hull and East Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust, (b) Yorkshire Ambulance Service NHS Trust and (c) Humber NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648756","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>The NHS Constitution asks patients to recognise that they can make a significant contribution to their own health and wellbeing, and take personal responsibility for it.</p><p> </p><p>The Handbook to the NHS Constitution states: “The right to treatment within 18 weeks from referral will cease to apply in circumstances where… delaying the start of your treatment is in your best clinical interests, for example where smoking cessation or weight management is likely to improve the outcome of the treatment.”</p><p> </p><p>The handbook can be found at the following address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/474450/NHS_Constitution_Handbook_v2.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/474450/NHS_Constitution_Handbook_v2.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>NHS Vale of York Clinical Commissioning Group is fully committed to ensuring local clinicians make decisions to ensure the best clinical outcome for patients – we know that smokers and obese patients are at greater risk of harm from surgical interventions.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-08T13:43:56.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648756/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648756/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648756/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Surgery: Vale of York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of whether the NHS Vale of York Clinical Commissioning Group's plans to delay treatments for obese patients and smokers is consistent with the NHS Constitution.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648757","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) are being developed by local areas. The North West London STP footprint estimates that its plan will produce £570 million of ‘business as usual’ savings based on NHS England’s counterfactual set out in the Five Year Forward View, the majority delivered by the acute providers through joint working and without strategic change.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, the plan also estimates that changing service provision will deliver £303 million of clinical commissioning group commissioner savings and £143 million of provider savings, subject to capital investment.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-05T16:39:42.53Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648757/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648757/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648757/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Health Services: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the amount of efficiency savings to be found under the North West London Sustainability and Transformation Plan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","55582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648758","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are responsible for commissioning care to provide the best possible outcomes for their patients, while also effectively managing their resources.</p><p> </p><p>It is for the Vale of York CCG to review the impact of its decisions on patients, while also taking into account the best practice and relevant clinical guidance.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-07T15:16:44.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648758/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648758/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Surgery: Vale of York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will publish correspondence between NHS England and Vale of York Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) on the recent review into that CCG's policy of delaying treatment for obese patients and smokers.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648760","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>Data is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information showing the counts and percentages of outpatient appointments with the treatment specialty ‘ophthalmology’, broken down by attendance type, for clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) of treatment, NHS Blackpool CCG and NHS Fylde and Wyre CCG, in 2015-16, is shown in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p>CCG</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>NHS Blackpool</p></td><td colspan="2"><p>NHS Fylde and Wyre</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Attendance Type</p></td><td><p>Counts</p></td><td><p>Percentages</p></td><td><p>Counts</p></td><td><p>Percentages</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Attended</p></td><td><p>52,532</p></td><td><p>64.8%</p></td><td><p>252</p></td><td><p>66.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cancelled by provider</p></td><td><p>12,871</p></td><td><p>15.9%</p></td><td><p>14</p></td><td><p>3.7%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cancelled by patient</p></td><td><p>10,792</p></td><td><p>13.3%</p></td><td><p>42</p></td><td><p>11.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Patient did not attend</p></td><td><p>4,806</p></td><td><p>5.9%</p></td><td><p>74</p></td><td><p>19.4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Not known</p></td><td><p>88</p></td><td><p>0.1%</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>0.0%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>81,089</p></td><td><p>100.0%</p></td><td><p>382</p></td><td><p>100.0%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Hospital Episode Statistics (HES), NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p><em>Notes: </em></p><p> </p><ol><li>Activity in English National Health Service hospitals and English NHS commissioned activity in the independent sector.</li><li>Outpatient appointments: The number of booked appointments for outpatients. They are recorded as one row per appointment that was made, whether it was attended or not. A patient's treatment in outpatients can consist of a series of appointments; a distinction between the first in the series and subsequent appointments is commonly reported. ‘Counts’ are not counts of people as the same person may have had more than one appointment within the same period.</li><li>Treatment Specialty: The code used to identify ophthalmology treatment specialty is 130 – Ophthalmology.</li><li>Attendance type: Identifies if the patient attended an appointment, if it was first or subsequent attendance, if the appointment was cancelled or the patient did not attend.</li><li>CCG of treatment: This indicates the CCG area within which the organisation providing treatment was located. The providers with sites mapped to each CCG of treatment are:</li></ol><p> </p><p>NHS Blackpool CCG:</p><p> </p><p>- Whitegate Health Centre</p><p>- Inhealth Diagnostics (Glenroyd Medical Centre)</p><p>- Aintree University Hospital NHS Foundation Trust</p><p>- Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust</p><p>- Specsavers Hearcare – Lancashire – Blackpool</p><p>- Glenroyd Medical Practice</p><p>- Blackpool Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust</p><p>- Virgin Care Blackpool LLP</p><p>- Spire Fylde Coast Hospital</p><p> </p><p>NHS Fylde and Wear CCG:</p><p> </p><p>- Blackpool Teaching Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust</p><p>- Specsavers Hearcare – Lancashire - Kirkham</p><p>- Specsavers Hearcare – Lancashire - Fleetwood</p><p>- Lancashire Care NHS Foundation Trust</p><p>- Specsavers Hearcare – Lancashire – St Anne’s</p><p>- Specsavers Hearcare – Lancashire - Cleveleys</p><p> </p><ol start="6"><li>Please note that CCG of treatment is based on the site of treatment, and some hospital providers may have sites in both of the CCGs.</li><li>The reporting period for 2015-16 is 1 April 2015 to 31 March 2016.</li></ol>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-07T15:31:02.423Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648760/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648760/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Ophthalmology: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of ophthalmology appointments were cancelled or delayed by hospitals in (a) NHS Blackpool Clinical Commissioning Group and (b) NHS Fylde and Wyre Clinical Commissioning Group in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","55599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648761","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) are being developed by local areas. The North West London STP sets out a strategic overview for the health economy of North West London, and does not include details of bed numbers.</p><p> </p><p>The Implementation Business Case will be published on 6 December, setting out the capital ask for investment into North West London. It will include some modelling on bed numbers.</p><p> </p><p>The case will propose significant investment in healthcare across the whole of North West London including in hospitals, out of hospital hubs and general practitioner surgeries.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-05T16:29:46.027Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648761/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648761/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hospital Beds: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on plans to make changes to the number of hospital beds as part of the North West London Sustainability and Transformation Plan; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","55581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648762","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>Work is ongoing on the detailed design of a new scheme, to secure appropriate support for those infected with HIV and hepatitis C. The standards of care provided by the National Health Service will continue.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-07T10:32:56.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648762/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648762/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that people diagnosed with HIV infection will retain the same standards of care under the new structuring of contaminated blood payment structure as they do at present.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648763","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>Nationally funded work on HIV through the charitable and voluntary sector is focused on prevention of infection in those at higher risk of acquiring HIV.</p><p> </p><p>The HIV Prevention Innovation Fund is open to voluntary sector organisations to deliver projects, preferably of up to 12 months duration, that explore new ways to address high risk behaviours in those communities most affected by HIV. A total of £0.6 million was allocated to the fund in 2016/17 and addressing HIV-associated stigma was identified as one of the priorities. This is only one element of our funding for HIV Prevention and Sexual Health Promotion for which there is £2.5 million funding in 2016/17.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-08T15:31:39.15Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648763/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648763/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funding his Department provides to charities and trusts that support people diagnosed with HIV.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648764","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>Under the existing NHS Bursary scheme which eligible pre-registration healthcare students can access for courses that start before 1 August 2017, the NHS Business Services Authority estimate the number of nursing students applying for funding for courses starting in January 2017 will be in the range of 1,300 to 1,350.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-05T15:37:16.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648764/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648764/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of nursing students who will apply for student finance for courses starting in January 2017.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","55637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648765","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>There are currently three charities that support those infected with HIV and hepatitis C infection through National Health Service supplied blood and blood products, namely; the Eileen Trust, the Caxton Foundation and the McFarlane Trust. However, these trusts are funded through allocations directed by annual letters from the Department rather than Government grants.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-07T10:30:56.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648765/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648765/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many charitable trusts that specialise in supporting people who have received contaminated blood are solely funded by Government grants.","false","Biography information for Karen Lumley","Redditch","Karen Lumley","55622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648766","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>NHS-funded Nursing Care is the funding provided by the National Health Service to homes providing nursing to support the provision of nursing care by a registered nurse.</p><p> </p><p>Where an individual has been assessed as eligible for NHS-funded Nursing Care, it is the responsibility of the relevant NHS clinical commissioning group to ensure that the weekly rate of £156.25 is passed on to the care provider in full, including making arrangements to backdate the rate to 1 April 2016 for individuals who were eligible at this time.</p><p> </p><p>Section 22 of the Care Act 2014 makes clear that the costs of providing nursing care by a registered nurse are the responsibility of the NHS, rather than of the local authority or of those individuals who are funding their own care.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","55639","2016-12-05T13:44:16.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648766/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648766/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Care Homes: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether it is the responsibility of nursing homes to backdate the increased rate for NHS funded nursing care to April 2016.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","55638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648767","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>NHS-funded Nursing Care is the funding provided by the National Health Service to homes providing nursing to support the provision of nursing care by a registered nurse.</p><p> </p><p>Where an individual has been assessed as eligible for NHS-funded Nursing Care, it is the responsibility of the relevant NHS clinical commissioning group to ensure that the weekly rate of £156.25 is passed on to the care provider in full, including making arrangements to backdate the rate to 1 April 2016 for individuals who were eligible at this time.</p><p> </p><p>Section 22 of the Care Act 2014 makes clear that the costs of providing nursing care by a registered nurse are the responsibility of the NHS, rather than of the local authority or of those individuals who are funding their own care.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","55638","2016-12-05T13:44:16.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648767/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648767/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Care Homes: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the ability of local authorities to cover the increase of £44.25 per week announced for NHS funded nursing care.","false","Biography information for Anne Marie Morris","Newton Abbot","Anne Marie Morris","55639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648768","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Department does not have an overall estimate of uncollected fees relating to the use of the National Health Service by patients subject to charge under section 175 of the NHS Act 2006, either by region or nationality of debtor. NHS Trust and NHS Foundation trust annual accounts provide information on provisions and debt that has been written off, however this does not give the total debt picture because some of these amounts will be paid in subsequent years.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T10:35:01.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648768/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648768/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the amount owed to NHS trusts in Yorkshire and the Humber by non-EU nationals for health care they have received on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","55601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648769","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>The quality of fire detection and alarm systems or information relating to fire compartmentation in National Health Service premises in England, are not areas inspected by the Care Quality Commission (CQC), nor is this information collected by the Department.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC is concerned with the safety and quality of treatment for patients and the fundamental standards are based around Person Centred care; treating the patients with dignity and respect, the need for consent to treatment, and the meeting the nutritional needs of patients. The CQC does check premises and (medical) equipment but this is around making sure the premises are clean, secure, and suitable for the purpose for which they are being used rather than looking into any evacuation processes.</p><p> </p><p>Fire detection and alarm systems and fire compartmentation are matters enforced by local fire and rescue services under the Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005. The CQC is not the enforcing authority for these regulations.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-05T15:44:19.13Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648769/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648769/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hospitals: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospitals have been found to have poor (a) fire detection systems and (b) fire separation provision by the Care Quality Commission in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","55704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648770","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p> </p><p>However the National Confidential Inquiry into Suicide and Homicide by People with Mental Illness collected information on the number of estimated and confirmed inpatient suicides in England from 2004 to 2014. This information can be found in their latest report, which was published in October 2016:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://research.bmh.manchester.ac.uk/cmhs/research/centreforsuicideprevention/nci/reports/2016-report.pdf" target="_blank">http://research.bmh.manchester.ac.uk/cmhs/research/centreforsuicideprevention/nci/reports/2016-report.pdf</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-05T16:58:07.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648770/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648770/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Mental Patients: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many recorded suicides there have been among psychiatric hospital in-patients in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","55703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648771","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>The information is not available in the format requested. The attached table provided by NHS Digital shows figures for patients using National Health Service adult secondary mental health and learning disability services by clinical commissioning group of general practitioner practice or residence, for 2013/14, 2014/15 and an estimate figure for 2015/16.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-05T17:01:48.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648771/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648771/answer","161202 PQ55708 mental health diagnoses in Newham.xlsx","161202 PQ55708 mental health diagnoses in Newham.xlsx","PQ55708 mental health diagnoses in Newham","PQ55708 mental health diagnoses in Newham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648771/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Mental Illness: Newham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many mental health diagnoses were completed in (a) the London Borough of Newham and (b) East Ham constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","55708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648772","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>No trust has been placed into special measures in 2016 solely as a consequence of the condition of its estate.</p><p> </p><p>Trusts are placed in special measures by NHS Improvement usually following a recommendation by the Chief Inspector of Hospitals. A decision to recommend quality special measures is based upon the Care Quality Commission’s (CQC) comprehensive inspection report for the trust. The CQC inspects the estate of a provider under the ‘Safe’ key question and is one of many areas that the CQC monitors when conducting an inspection of a provider.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T10:37:30.807Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648772/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648772/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hospitals: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospital sites and accompanying facilities have been placed in special measures as a result of poor building conditions in 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55669"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648773","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of hospital trusts that use some form of homeopathic treatment in their services or information on how much funding the National Health Service has allocated for the use of homeopathic treatments as requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not maintain a position on any particular complementary or alternative medicine treatments, including homeopathy. It is the responsibility of local NHS organisations to make decisions on the commissioning and funding of any health care treatments for NHS patients, such as homeopathy, taking account of safety, clinical and cost effectiveness and the availability of suitably qualified/regulated practitioners.</p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the United States administration's decision to require scientific evidence before confirming availability of the medical use of homeopathy on the Department’s current policy.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55657 ; 55658 ; 55667","2016-12-06T10:31:52.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648773/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648773/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much funding the NHS has allocated for the use of homeopathic treatments in each year from 2011-12 to the current financial year.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648774","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of hospital trusts that use some form of homeopathic treatment in their services or information on how much funding the National Health Service has allocated for the use of homeopathic treatments as requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not maintain a position on any particular complementary or alternative medicine treatments, including homeopathy. It is the responsibility of local NHS organisations to make decisions on the commissioning and funding of any health care treatments for NHS patients, such as homeopathy, taking account of safety, clinical and cost effectiveness and the availability of suitably qualified/regulated practitioners.</p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the United States administration's decision to require scientific evidence before confirming availability of the medical use of homeopathy on the Department’s current policy.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55657 ; 55658 ; 55668","2016-12-06T10:31:52.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648774/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648774/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential implications of his policies of the US administration's decision to require scientific evidence before confirming availability of the medical use of homeopathy.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648776","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>No capital funding has been transferred to current (revenue) spending for 2016-17. Any such transfer would be reviewed and finalised through the Supplementary Estimate processes.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T10:39:09.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648776/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648776/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Department of Health: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what level of capital funding his Department has transferred to current spending for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648777","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>Detailed best practice guidance was made available to local systems to support implementation of the 2016/17 Accident &amp; Emergency (A&amp;E) Improvement plan. This guidance was a collection of best practice models for local systems to identify which would be most effective for them to implement in support of their A&amp;E Improvement Plans, rather than a formal nationally issued piece of guidance for all local systems to adopt in its entirety.</p><p> </p><p>This guidance advises that general practitioners should respond appropriately to requests for home visits. General practices should have processes in place to respond to and prioritise requests for urgent home visits, usually through early telephone assessment and a duty doctor rota. Again, this is for local determination.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-07T15:18:20.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648777/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648777/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","General Practitioners: Home Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department has given to GPs on emergency home visits during Winter 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648778","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>NHS Digital collects data on turnover for nursing staff and surgeons working in the National Health Service. The attached table shows how many people leave or join the NHS each month as a proportion of all in the particular group in that month. Numbers are shown for each nursing band and for associate specialist, specialty doctor, staff grade doctor and consultant surgeons from January 2016. Numbers of staff moving between grades or across organisations within the NHS are not included.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-08T13:50:43.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648778/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648778/answer","PQ55664- Turnover to the nurse group and surgical group.xlsx","PQ55664- Turnover to the nurse group and surgical group.xlsx","PQ55664- Turnover to the nurse group and surgical ","PQ55664- Turnover to the nurse group and surgical ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648778/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Health Professions: Labour Turnover","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the turnover of NHS staff was in each band of (a) nurse and (b) surgeon in each month from January 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648779","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>Information on National Health Service sites across England that have reported backlog maintenance costs is collected annually from the NHS through the Estates Return Information Collection system and is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>This information is not amended centrally. Therefore, the NHS organisations that have provided the data are responsible for its completeness and accuracy.</p><p> </p><p>NHS organisations locally are responsible for the safety and quality of their estate as well as the management of their own backlog maintenance, including high-risk repairs. They decide on the investment needed to maintain their estate. We will invest more than £20 billion on capital over the next five years including for maintenance of estate, new buildings and equipment, to ensure NHS facilities meet the highest possible standards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","55659","2016-12-08T10:58:20.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648779/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648779/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hospitals: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate the NHS has made of the cost of high risk repairs in each month from January 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648780","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>NHS Vale of York Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG) has regular and ongoing discussions with NHS England (Yorkshire and the Humber regional team).</p><p> </p><p>The CCG aims to fully implement National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance in all its policies, to ensure its plans are clinically appropriate for patients.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-07T15:14:44.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648780/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648780/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Surgery: Vale of York","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with (a) NHS England and (b) NICE on the NHS Vale of York Clinical Commissioning Group's plans to delay treatments for obese patients and smokers.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","55646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648781","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>Information on National Health Service sites across England that have reported backlog maintenance costs is collected annually from the NHS through the Estates Return Information Collection system and is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://hefs.hscic.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>This information is not amended centrally. Therefore, the NHS organisations that have provided the data are responsible for its completeness and accuracy.</p><p> </p><p>NHS organisations locally are responsible for the safety and quality of their estate as well as the management of their own backlog maintenance, including high-risk repairs. They decide on the investment needed to maintain their estate. We will invest more than £20 billion on capital over the next five years including for maintenance of estate, new buildings and equipment, to ensure NHS facilities meet the highest possible standards.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","55665","2016-12-08T10:58:17.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648781/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648781/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hospitals: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many hospital sites across England have backlog maintenance costs of £10 million or more; and how many of those hospital sites are assessed as high risk on that account.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648782","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>This is an operational matter for trusts, clinical commissioning groups and their local partners. NHS England and NHS Improvement have provided guidance to all National Health Service organisations to ensure there are robust plans in place for winter which are assured regionally and nationally.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England published the Operational Pressures Escalation Levels Framework in October 2016. This guidance provides best practice around triggers and actions to be taken when considering escalation in response to operational pressures, as well as protocols and standardised terminology to follow.</p><p> </p><p>The guidance is available at the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/operational-pressures-escalation-levels-framework.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/operational-pressures-escalation-levels-framework.pdf</a></p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T10:41:20.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648782/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648782/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hospital Beds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether his Department has offered guidance to NHS trusts on how to deal with potential black alerts during winter 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648783","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-07T10:36:14.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648783/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648783/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hospitals: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of hospital procedures that have been transferred to private contractors by each NHS Trust in each month in 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648784","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of hospital trusts that use some form of homeopathic treatment in their services or information on how much funding the National Health Service has allocated for the use of homeopathic treatments as requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not maintain a position on any particular complementary or alternative medicine treatments, including homeopathy. It is the responsibility of local NHS organisations to make decisions on the commissioning and funding of any health care treatments for NHS patients, such as homeopathy, taking account of safety, clinical and cost effectiveness and the availability of suitably qualified/regulated practitioners.</p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the United States administration's decision to require scientific evidence before confirming availability of the medical use of homeopathy on the Department’s current policy.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55658 ; 55667 ; 55668","2016-12-06T10:31:52.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648784/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648784/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on how many hospital trusts use some form of homeopathic treatment in their services.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648786","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department does not hold information on the number of hospital trusts that use some form of homeopathic treatment in their services or information on how much funding the National Health Service has allocated for the use of homeopathic treatments as requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not maintain a position on any particular complementary or alternative medicine treatments, including homeopathy. It is the responsibility of local NHS organisations to make decisions on the commissioning and funding of any health care treatments for NHS patients, such as homeopathy, taking account of safety, clinical and cost effectiveness and the availability of suitably qualified/regulated practitioners.</p><p> </p><p>No assessment has been made of the United States administration's decision to require scientific evidence before confirming availability of the medical use of homeopathy on the Department’s current policy.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55657 ; 55667 ; 55668","2016-12-06T10:31:52.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648786/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648786/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department gives to NHS trusts on the allocation of their funds for homeopathic treatment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648787","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>NHS England publishes the number of Category A Red One and Red Two calls responded to within eight minutes and the number of call-outs that receive a face to face response from the ambulance service. This data is published on a monthly basis at both an England national level and at individual ambulance trust level. Data up to September 2016, <em>Ambulance System Indicators Time Series to September 2016</em> is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ambulance-quality-indicators/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ambulance-quality-indicators/</a></p><p> </p><p>Ambulance services are facing unprecedented demand for their services. To address this, NHS England is exploring, as part of its Ambulance Response Programme, whether changes to the way that the ambulance service responds to calls could help improve response times to critically ill patients and improve outcomes for all patients who contact the ambulance service. As a result, the data published on ambulance performance is no longer consistent or available for all trusts.</p><p> </p><p>Health is a devolved matter in the rest of the United Kingdom.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","55670","2016-12-07T10:34:24.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648787/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648787/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Ambulance Services: Emergency Calls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the performance of each ambulance service in reaching severe patient call-outs within eight minutes; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648788","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-05T17:00:46.64Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648788/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648788/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Personality Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many and what proportion of people diagnosed with Borderline Personality Disorder received Mentalisation Based Therapy in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","55783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648789","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>In relation to monitoring performance, in October 2016, NHS England published a Mental Health Five Year Forward View Dashboard. The dashboard includes metrics for monitoring key performance and outcomes data and will be updated quarterly.</p><p> </p><p>£11.7 billion was an NHS England estimate of mental health spending in 2014/15, based on a bespoke data collection. From 2014/15 clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) have been asked to return financial data on total mental health spend, spend against additional allocations, and how this spend is split at a programme level. Additional guidance has been provided to CCGs to improve consistency of reporting. This financial data has been included in NHS England’s mental health dashboard.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-05T17:04:13.86Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648789/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648789/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Mental Health Services: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to his Department's response of 28 September 2016 to the petition Make more awareness and help available for young men dealing with mental health, what the evidential basis was for his estimate that annual mental health spending had increased to £11.7 billion.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","55779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648790","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>Planned spend for secure inpatient mental health services is based on contracts negotiated during the planning round so by default NHS England only set plans at the level of total mental health spend (at provider level) not at individual service line level. However, the outturn for specialised commissioning of secure inpatient mental health services is contained within the below table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Outturn</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£1,317 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£1,281 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-05T16:30:15.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648790/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648790/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Secure Psychiatric Units: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 30 November 2016 to Question 54960, what the (a) outturn and (b) planned spend was for specialist commissioning of secure inpatient mental health services in 2014-15 and 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","55780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648791","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>NHS England and the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence have advised that no extensions to the implementation period were requested as part of these technology appraisals.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-05T16:59:49.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648791/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648791/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Hepatitis: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 21 November 2016 to Question 53183, whether NHS England applied for an exemption from its legal requirement to make available ledipasvir-sofosbuvir (TA 363), ombitasvir-paritaprevir-ritonavir with or without ribavirin (TA 364) and daclastasvir (TA 365) within three months of the technology appraisal guidance being issued by NICE.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","55685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648792","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>In the Autumn Statement 2014 increased funding of £150 million over the next five years was announced to improve services for children and young people with mental health problems in England. Particular emphasis was placed on improving services for people with eating disorders. A prime focus of the work on eating disorders is about the improved provision of out of hospital care so patients are only admitted to a bed when clinically required.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has continued to commission additional specialised mental health beds to provide further capacity in areas where it is required. This includes 56 new Tier 4 beds, raising the total to 1,442, the highest this has been.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, NHS England is undertaking a pre-procurement review of Tier 4 services to ensure that the provision of mental health beds across the country supports improved access and care close to home where possible.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-06T16:18:48.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648792/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648792/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648792/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Eating Disorders: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps are being taken to ensure that young people diagnosed with eating disorders requiring in-patient treatment can be admitted to facilities close to home.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","55731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648793","Department of Health","false","2016-12-08","<p>Information on Government funding allocated to the Family Nurse Partnership (FNP) to cover costs of the FNP National Unit and local sites between 2006-08 and 2012-13 is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>£ million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006-08<sup>1</sup></p></td><td><p>6.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008-09<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>5.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009-10<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>10.30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>11.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>12.07</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13<sup>2</sup></p></td><td><p>10.99</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><sup>1</sup> Funded by the Department for Children Schools and Families. This covers two financial years.</p><p><sup>2</sup> Funded by the Department of Health.</p><p> </p><p>From 2013-14 only the costs of the national unit were funded centrally by the Government. Since then, FNP local sites have been funded by NHS England and local authorities and this information is not collected centrally.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-08T16:30:26.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648793/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648793/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Family Nurse Partnership Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much Government funding has been allocated to the Family Nurse Partnership in each year since that initiative was launched; and how many people worked in Family Nurse Partnerships in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","55732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648794","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>NHS England publishes the number of Category A Red One and Red Two calls responded to within eight minutes and the number of call-outs that receive a face to face response from the ambulance service. This data is published on a monthly basis at both an England national level and at individual ambulance trust level. Data up to September 2016, <em>Ambulance System Indicators Time Series to September 2016</em> is available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ambulance-quality-indicators/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ambulance-quality-indicators/</a></p><p> </p><p>Ambulance services are facing unprecedented demand for their services. To address this, NHS England is exploring, as part of its Ambulance Response Programme, whether changes to the way that the ambulance service responds to calls could help improve response times to critically ill patients and improve outcomes for all patients who contact the ambulance service. As a result, the data published on ambulance performance is no longer consistent or available for all trusts.</p><p> </p><p>Health is a devolved matter in the rest of the United Kingdom.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","55662","2016-12-07T10:34:24.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648794/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648794/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Ambulance Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many call-outs each ambulance service in the UK received in each month since January 2016; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","55670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648795","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>We have made no such assessment.</p><p> </p><p>In its clinical guideline on the diagnosis and treatment of early and locally advanced breast cancer (CG80), published in February 2009, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) recommends that bisphosphonates should be offered to patients for the management of breast cancer treatment-induced bone loss subject to certain criteria.</p><p> </p><p>NICE is currently updating this guidance and the use of adjuvant bisphosphonates is one of the key areas that will be covered in the update which is expected in July 2018.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-07T10:39:55.7Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648795/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648795/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-30","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has been made of the effectiveness of bisphosphates in the treatment of breast cancer.","false","Biography information for Nigel Dodds","Belfast North","Mr Nigel Dodds","55717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648796","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>We have a long established practice of not routinely commenting on individual immigration cases. Reasons for this include data protection.</p><p>We can however confirm that foreign nationals requiring leave to enter the UK must meet the requirements of the Immigration Rules in the category of entry sought and that, by their own actions, must not have brought themselves within scope of the general grounds for refusal in the Immigration Rules.</p><p>Evidence that an individual has been involved in organised crime or human rights abuses would be taken into account when a visa application is considered. Individuals will be denied entry to the UK where there is evidence to show that their presence would not be considered conducive to the public good.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","55730 ; 55739","2016-12-08T17:34:15.28Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648796/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648796/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Immigration Controls: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the 39 Russian nationals, named in the Sergei Magnitsky Rule of Law Accountability Act passed by the US Congress and President Obama in 2012, are currently barred from entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","55738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648797","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>We have a long established practice of not routinely commenting on individual immigration cases. Reasons for this include data protection.</p><p>We can however confirm that foreign nationals requiring leave to enter the UK must meet the requirements of the Immigration Rules in the category of entry sought and that, by their own actions, must not have brought themselves within scope of the general grounds for refusal in the Immigration Rules.</p><p>Evidence that an individual has been involved in organised crime or human rights abuses would be taken into account when a visa application is considered. Individuals will be denied entry to the UK where there is evidence to show that their presence would not be considered conducive to the public good.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","55730 ; 55738","2016-12-08T17:34:15.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648797/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648797/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Immigration Controls: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will issue orders barring the 39 Russian nationals, named in the Sergei Magnitsky Rule of Law Accountability Act passed by the US Congress and President Obama in 2012, from entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","55739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648798","Home Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>This Government is committed to attacking criminal finances and making the UK a more hostile environment for those who seek to move, hide and use the proceeds of crime and corruption.</p><p>To this end, the Government published its Action Plan for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist finance in April 2016. In October this year, the Criminal Finances Bill, which will implement key legislative elements of the Action Plan, was introduced to Parliament.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","55742","2016-12-05T17:06:29.607Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648798/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648798/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Money Laundering","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the implications of her Department's policies of the criminal complaint into money laundering filed with the National Crime Agency on 21 March 2016 by the Hermitage Fund; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","55765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648799","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>We have a long established practice of not routinely commenting on individual immigration cases. Reasons for this include data protection.</p><p>We can however confirm that foreign nationals requiring leave to enter the UK must meet the requirements of the Immigration Rules in the category of entry sought and that, by their own actions, must not have brought themselves within scope of the general grounds for refusal in the Immigration Rules.</p><p>Evidence that an individual has been involved in organised crime or human rights abuses would be taken into account when a visa application is considered. Individuals will be denied entry to the UK where there is evidence to show that their presence would not be considered conducive to the public good.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","55738 ; 55739","2016-12-08T17:34:15.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648799/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648799/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Pavel Karpov","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether there is an order in force that would prevent Pavel Karpov from entering the UK on or before 1 December 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","55730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648800","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>In all cases where an application under the family Immigration Rules fails to meet the minimum income threshold or other requirement, the decision maker will consider whether there are exceptional circumstances to warrant a grant of leave outside the Rules.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:35:50.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648800/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648800/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Entry Clearances: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her Department's policy to allow special considerations on the income threshold for the non-EEA partner of a British citizen if that partner is from a country experiencing war or conflict.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","55758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648801","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>Paragraphs 13(i) and 16 of Appendix FM-SE to the Immigration Rules ensure that a person is not disadvantaged by a period of maternity leave in meeting the minimum income threshold to sponsor a non-EEA partner to come to or remain in the UK.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:36:18.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648801/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648801/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Entry Clearances: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will take into account the implications for UK citizens with non-EEA partners of the effect of periods of maternity leave on the ability of those citizens to meet the income threshold in her decisions on immigration cases.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","55759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648802","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The earning potential of the non-EEA national partner is no guarantee that they will find work in the UK. Those with an appropriate job offer here can apply under Tier 2 of the Points Based System. Non-EEA national partners coming to the UK under the family route must be capable of being independently supported by their sponsor or by their joint savings or non-employment income.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:39:24.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648802/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648802/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Entry Clearances: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the implications for her Department's policy on the minimum income requirement for UK citizens with non-EEA partners of using evidence provided by those citizens of their partners' earning potential when making immigration decisions.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","55760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648803","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The minimum income threshold of £18,600 for sponsoring a non-EEA national partner to come or remain here applies across the UK. The level of the income threshold, which aims to prevent burdens on the taxpayer and promote integration, was set following advice from the independent Migration Advisory Committee and reflects the income at which a family settled here generally cannot access income-related benefits. The Committee, in its November 2011 report, could see no clear case for differentiation of the income threshold between UK countries and regions and noted several arguments against such an approach. These included that a family living in a wealthy part of a relatively poor UK country or region could be subject to a lower income requirement than a family living in a deprived part of a relatively wealthy one. The Government agrees with that assessment and applying a single minimum income threshold across the UK has been found to be lawful by the courts.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:39:51.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648803/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648803/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Entry Clearances: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the potential effect of applying regional income thresholds to UK citizens with non-EEA partners on the ability of those citizens to bring their partners to the UK.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","55761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648805","Home Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>This Government is committed to attacking criminal finances and making the UK a more hostile environment for those who seek to move, hide and use the proceeds of crime and corruption.</p><p>To this end, the Government published its Action Plan for anti-money laundering and counter-terrorist finance in April 2016. In October this year, the Criminal Finances Bill, which will implement key legislative elements of the Action Plan, was introduced to Parliament.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","55765","2016-12-05T17:06:29.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648805/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648805/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Foreign Investment in UK: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether she has made an assessment of the implications for her Department's policies of evidence to the Home Affairs Select Committee by Mr Williams Browder on 3 May 2016 on use of funds raised through criminal activity in Russia for investment in the UK; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","55742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648806","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>The information requested is published in quarterly statistics from table vi_06_q_w in Immigration Statistics, July – September 2016, in line with Ministerial guidance. https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2016/list-of-tables#visas</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-08T16:11:25.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648806/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648806/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Visas: Russia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many investor visas have been granted to Russian nationals since 2006.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Mitchell","Sutton Coldfield","Mr Andrew Mitchell","55767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648807","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-08","<p>It is important to make clear that the changes referred to will only affect claimants on Universal Credit Full service – they will not affect those on Housing Benefit. Since the policy was initially announced, we have worked in collaboration with key housing stakeholders such as Crisis and Shelter to make sure the policy includes the right exemptions to protect the most vulnerable people; we are therefore confident about the robustness of the policy.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-08T12:18:16.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648807/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648807/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-30","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether savings to the public purse over the current Parliament, which his Department estimated will accrue from changes in housing benefit for people under 21 years of age includes the costs of evictions and temporary accommodation potentially resulting from those changes; and whether he has made an assessment of the effect of those changes on young peoples' labour mobility.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","55656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648808","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>Destitute non-EEA nationals who have leave, or had leave, to enter or remain as a partner of a British citizen or person settled here and who claim to be victims of domestic abuse may apply under the provisions of the Destitute Domestic Violence Concession to access public funds, which may include access to refuges and multi agency support. This applies equally to those who are cohabiting with their partner and have valid leave to remain in the United Kingdom and those whose period of limited leave to enter or remain has expired.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-08T16:12:05.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648808/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648808/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Domestic Abuse: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether women are able to take refuge under domestic violence legislation if they continue to cohabit with their partner after the expiry of their initial leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","55713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648809","Home Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>We do not hold information centrally on the number of illegal foreign registered vehicles seized and impounded by Lancashire Constabulary. This is an operational matter for the police and other partner agencies.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-12-19T17:49:45.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648809/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648809/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Motor Vehicles: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 18 November 2016 to Question 50859, how many foreign-registered cars were seized and impounded by Lancashire Constabulary in England in each month between 1 January 2015 and 30 September 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","55636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648810","Home Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>No decisions have been made and no formal assessments have been made regarding the future of the UK passport. All relevant areas of policy and operational delivery surrounding changes to the UK passport will be considered when appropriate to do so.</p><p>Parliament will be informed in due course about any changes to the UK passport.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-12-07T16:55:59.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648810/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648810/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648810/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 9 November 2016 to Question 47644, if she will clarify whether an assessment of the (a) legal and (b) financial obstacles to changing the colour of UK passports informed her decision.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","55575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648811","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>Border controls at Heathrow are among the most stringent in the world. Border Force employs a rigorous and effective control regime at the UK’s borders, predicated on a policy of carrying out full checks of all arriving passengers and an intelligence-led approach to searching for contraband goods that ensures resources are used as effectively as possible. Border Force Heathrow has transformed its working practices, command and control and leadership in order to keep the UK safe.</p><p>We have also invested in new technology to enhance security and improve the service delivered to legitimate passengers and deliver efficiencies. 55 ePassport Gates are operational across Heathrow terminals. A total of 8.8 million passengers used the ePassport gates at Heathrow in the past year (to end of October 2016), which represents 64.3% of eligible passengers. This is a 27% increase from the same period ending October 2015.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-08T19:02:27.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648811/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648811/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Immigration Controls: Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment she has made of the adequacy of levels of Border Control officers at Heathrow Airport; and what steps she is taking to increase those levels.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","55565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648812","Home Office","false","2016-12-19","<p>In the last 12 months the number of egates at Heathrow has been significantly increased, rising from 25 to 55 across the 4 terminals, with a further 9 due to go live at T5 in January 2017. In the last 12 months nearly 9 million passengers have used the gates at Heathrow. The gates continue to meet their agreed service level agreements for availability. Efficiencies are derived from the fact passengers using a bank of 5 gates can be monitored by a single officer and by the egates offering a quicker service to passengers through the border. Supplementary measures are also in place to ensure Border Force Security objectives are met.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-19T10:17:50.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648812/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648812/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Immigration Controls: Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what recent assessment her Department has made of the efficiency and effective working of E-passport checking machines at Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","55566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648813","Home Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Government Car Service stopped providing individual cars in April 2012. Therefore, there is no individual journey data available from 1 April 2012. The Department for Transport, as part of their transparency agenda, publishes information on the costs incurred by each government department through the use of vehicles provided by the Government Car Services.</p><p>Information on recent years can be found via the Gov.UK website below:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/ministerial-cars</p><p>The information on 2011-2012 financial year can be found via link below:</p><p>https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2012-12-20/debates/12122056000014/GovernmentCarAndDespatchAgency</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-12-07T16:36:36.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648813/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648813/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Home Office: Government Car Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much her Department spent on providing vehicles for each Minister through the Government Car Service in each year from 2011 to 2016 to date.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","55551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648816","Home Office","false","2016-12-06","<p>The UK is a world-leader in the fight to stamp out the brutal practice of forced marriage, with our joint Home Office and Foreign and Commonwealth Office Forced Marriage Unit (FMU) which leads efforts to combat it both at home and abroad. We made forced marriage a criminal offence in 2014 to better protect victims and send a clear message that this abhorrent practice is totally unacceptable and will not be tolerated in the UK.</p><p>The FMU acts in an advisory capacity and, where there is an imminent risk of serious harm or threat to life to the victim, will refer cases to the police and other statutory agencies as appropriate.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-12-06T16:35:34.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648816/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648816/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Forced Marriage Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what protocols are in place for the Forced Marriage Unit to provide information to local constabularies about people referred to them.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","55552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648817","Home Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Coalition Government signed the Istanbul Convention to show its strong commitment to tackling violence against women and girls, and this Government remains committed to ratifying it.</p><p>In most respects, the measures already in place in the UK to protect women and girls from violence comply with or go further than the Convention requires.</p><p>Further amendments to domestic law, to take extra-territorial jurisdiction over a range of offences, are necessary before the Convention can be ratified. We will seek to legislate when the approach to implementing the extra-territorial jurisdiction requirements in England and Wales is agreed and Parliamentary time allows.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2016-12-07T16:48:07.45Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648817/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648817/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Council of Europe Convention on Preventing and Combating Violence against Women and Domestic Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what process the Government plans to use for the ratification of the Istanbul Convention.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","55560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648819","Department for Transport","false","2016-12-07","<p>Arrangements for the provision of lighthouses and other aids to navigation sit outside of European Union regulations under the international convention on Safety of Lives at Sea (SOLAS) managed by the International Maritime Organization.</p><p> </p><p>The provision of all aids to navigation safety for Northern Ireland is the responsibility of the Commissioners of Irish Lights. The Commissioners of Irish Lights have responsibility for aids to navigation for the whole of the island of Ireland and are accountable to the UK Department for Transport for their operations in UK waters. No change to this arrangement is envisaged as a result of the UK’s exit from the European Union.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-12-07T15:37:07.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648819/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648819/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-11-30","Lighthouses: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to take steps to gain jurisdiction over lighthouses on islands off the coast of Northern Ireland after the UK's exit from the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","55631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648820","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>Both policing and the fire service are devolved in Scotland and Northern Ireland.</p><p>Council tax policy in Wales is a matter for the Welsh government. Council tax referendum principles for local authorities in England are set by the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government and are subject to the approval of the House of Commons. An announcement about principles for 2017/18 will, be made shortly.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-12-08T15:49:55.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648820/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648820/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Police and Fire and Rescue Services: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the taxation levels of front-line police and fire services across the constituent parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","55627"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648821","Home Office","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Government has brought forward legislative amendments to the 1992 Firefighters’ Pension Scheme to address this issue in England, which came into force on 30 September 2016. These amendments ensure that a firefighter who accrues maximum pensionable service in the scheme will be entitled to a pension contributions holiday until they reach the age of 50.</p><p>The provision applies retrospectively to 1 December 2006 and affected firefighters may be entitled to a refund of some of their contributions. Fire and Rescue Authorities are expected to make the majority of those refund payments by the end of March 2017.</p><p>The Devolved Administrations have responsibility for firefighters’ pension schemes in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-12-05T17:18:40.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648821/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648821/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-30","Fire and Rescue Services: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what progress she has made on plans to bring forward legislative proposals to support firefighters who joined the Firefighters Pension Scheme 1992 before the age of 20 who were required to continue paying pension contributions beyond the maximum entitlement before drawing their pension.","false","Biography information for Corri Wilson","Ayr, Carrick and Cumnock","Corri Wilson","55573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648822","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-12-08","<p>A successful procurement process was concluded in June 2016 for a new annunciator system. As part of phase one of this project, we anticipate the new software will be rolled out by Easter 2017. The system has been specified in such a way that it will enable delivery of the data to mobile devices as part of phase two of this project. A delivery date for phase two has yet to be agreed.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-12-08T11:48:20.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648822/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648822/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-11-30","House of Commons Annunciator System: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Rt. hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, with reference to the Answer of 12 May 2016 to Question 36829, on House of Commons Annunciator System: Internet, when procurement for that system will be completed; and when he expects that system to be in operation.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","55714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648823","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Partnership Principles are largely focused on our assessment of, and work with, partner governments and are not directly relevant to CDC, which invests in the private sector not governments.</p><p>In countries where DFID has a country office, CDC and DFID liaise, consult, and share knowledge in a mutually agreed manner on the sectors and/or industries in those countries, states or territories which have the greatest developmental need.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-12-05T18:08:49.307Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648823/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648823/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-30","Commonwealth Development Corporation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department's Partnership Principles apply to the Commonwealth Development Corporation.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","55648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648824","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-05","<p>CDC has their own internal audit function which reports to the Board. As noted in the recent NAO report four cases were referred jointly to CDC and DFID, and CDC consulted informally with DFID on a further three allegations.</p><p>One of these cases – the allegations regarding ECP made in 2010 – is in the public domain. We cannot comment on other allegations.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-12-05T18:06:33.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648824/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648824/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-30","Commonwealth Development Corporation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the value and nature was of each example of fraud and corruption identified by her Department's internal audit of the Commonwealth Development Corporation Group's internal audit mechanisms in Commonwealth Development in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","55649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648825","Department for International Development","false","2016-12-07","<p>Our partners, including the UN and non-governmental organisations, conduct regular needs assessments, inside and outside of camps. This helps us to reach the most vulnerable people in Iraq with UK-funded assistance.</p><p>Since June 2014, the UK has committed £169.5 million of humanitarian funding to Iraq. Our support to a range of partners enables UK aid to respond to the most pressing needs both inside and outside of camps, through the provision of clean water, food, medicines, protection services, and cash assistance. The UK is the largest donor to the UN Iraq Humanitarian Pooled Fund, which is flexible and responsive to the most urgent humanitarian needs.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-12-07T18:15:14.613Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648825/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/648825/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-11-30","Iraq: Internally Displaced People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to identify the needs of displaced people living outside the camp structure in Iraq; and what humanitarian support her Department is providing to those such people.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","55644"
